[{'created': '2015-09-22 00:46:56.000000000', 'message': 'Log message when debug is enabled

Operators may not realize that when debug is enabled that keystone
will return extra, potentially sensitive, data in error responses.

Operators should at least be warned that this will happen.

SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I82d00898ee2b28aad1ace7554a436cf7125d631c
'}]
commit_message:
Log message when debug is enabled

Operators may not realize that when debug is enabled that keystone
will return extra, potentially sensitive, data in error responses.

Operators should at least be warned that this will happen.

SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I82d00898ee2b28aad1ace7554a436cf7125d631c

commit_message:
Tempest: use mkdtemp to make temp directories

generate_random_name() was used instead of mkdtemp to create temporary
directories, with no check on existence. This fixes that.

Change-Id: I69c49e146ef1edca2b6fac0c0a9a06e158db160c

commit_message:
Raise container deployment timeout

If yum repository configuration is partially broken,
it will delay deployment time. The time should be
raised to match the dockerctl timeout of 400s.

Change-Id: Icc68f039362d7c3f08c532add14d24f2140b8e3d
Closes-Bug: #1494640

commit_message:
Add missing libvirt section to nova.conf

This is required to boot VMs using Nova. Add a sane default to the
template to suit most, and make it easier for those who want something
else to see where to override.

Change-Id: I898862b905289cc30ad447f0ef81895c93ff2478
Closes-Bug: #1496931

commit_message:
Enable back cover job

Rally 'cover' tox job runs against last two commits so, fix for
broken cover job was implemented with disabled job.
Now we need to enable it.

Change-Id: Id083b233ae072fa8e0a875dee74a33c6a3f51ec8
Partial-Bug: #1497897

commit_message:
Add option to set EPEL mirror

In some environments it may be desirable to set the EPEL
mirror to use. Add this ability.

Change-Id: Iefa22bde7a64b40e6d36ba39efa9102de9393e06

commit_message:
add ironic support:

 * Add new network 'ironic'
 * Add new role 'ironic_slave'. This VM looks like
   current 'slave' node, but it is connected ONLY
   to "ironic" network.
 * fix Node.interface_by_name method. Rename it to
   interface_by_network_name

Partially Implements: blueprint integrate-ironic-to-test-tools

Change-Id: Idd9ebca53c2cfd0df088c7d516f6285ad58fe7db

commit_message:
Parameter osapi_max_limit is always used by default

Default value max_limit is initialized before a value is read from
the config file. Default parameter values are always evaluated when
the “def” statement they belong to is executed. So parameter
osapi_max_limit is always used by default even it's set in the
configuration file.

Change-Id: I1414667d30e98b56c5eb1b09b802bab823b37e2d
Closes-Bug: #1487510

commit_message:
Using OpenStack CLI for supporting Keystone V3

Currently python-keystoneclient focuses on python API only and
python-openstackclient on CLI. This is certain trend now (ask from
keystone guys). So to enable more new features for example keystone v3
here, we need use openstackclient in devstack install scripts.

Notes:
python API means:
    # python scripts
    from keystoneclient import client as c
    c.Client(...).get_user_list(...)

CLI means:
    # bash/shell scripts
    keystone user-list

Closed-Bug: #1478763
Change-Id: Iee802c887994da7036fe206c1b2970c1006e273c

[{'created': '2015-09-18 20:29:55.000000000', 'message': "Relax service module check on service providers

service_provider is a 'special' configuration. It is a MultiStr
option that used to be in neutron.conf, but moved into its own *-aas
config files after the service split. We allow for the definition to
be available 'anywhere': either in neutron.conf or in the *-aas
service's config file.

The list of 'service_provider' can include drivers from within the *-aas
tree, or from elsewhere, and can apply to different service types. Due to
the polymorphic nature of this variable it is very tricky to identify only
the drivers that pertain a specific service module: the service module
may as well implement more than one service type and may have support
from drivers out of tree.

For this reason it is best to relax this check and rely on query filters
when the ServiceManager.get_service_providers() is invoked.

Closes-bug: #1492069

Change-Id: I4db4ce0b287c984d86181227edf769531ecb7bb8

commit_message:
Relax service module check on service providers

service_provider is a 'special' configuration. It is a MultiStr
option that used to be in neutron.conf, but moved into its own *-aas
config files after the service split. We allow for the definition to
be available 'anywhere': either in neutron.conf or in the *-aas
service's config file.

The list of 'service_provider' can include drivers from within the *-aas
tree, or from elsewhere, and can apply to different service types. Due to
the polymorphic nature of this variable it is very tricky to identify only
the drivers that pertain a specific service module: the service module
may as well implement more than one service type and may have support
from drivers out of tree.

For this reason it is best to relax this check and rely on query filters
when the ServiceManager.get_service_providers() is invoked. Furthermore,
without this fix there was a situation where the value returned by
'service_providers' may be differ depending on how the configuration is
passed on the CLI, and this inconsistency may only cause headaches.

Closes-bug: #1492069

Change-Id: I4db4ce0b287c984d86181227edf769531ecb7bb8

Switch config.mk to master branch for fuel projects

Due to bug[1] in Gerrit, 7.0-only patchset has been applied  to master. We
obviously want to track master in master branch…

[1] https://code.google.com/p/gerrit/issues/detail?id=1107

Change-Id: I1c7a86711295bcb677db6778f57ab016ce53f149
Related-bug: #1466640

commit_message:
Add introductory documentation for networking-bgpvpn

This change includes README.rst directly into the base index.rst rather
than including it by reference in readme.rst and removes readme.rst from
the ToC. It also expands on the introductory paragraph in preparation for
linking to the top level index.html from the parent OpenStack developer
web page (http://docs.openstack.org/developer/openstack-projects.html)

Change-Id: Ifde5fa734fc1301c57598ec36d53895e94881588

Remove some temporary variables not needed

In the orderedset code we can just remove these temp variables
and just inline them instead, making the code a little bit easier
to read.

[{'created': '2015-09-21 16:08:05.000000000', 'message': 'Fix leaking environment variables in tests.

In rspec provider tests the environment variables are used to
authenticate the calls.  The environment was set in a shared example.
The problem is that rspec read all those environment variables when it
compile the tests.  Then the last shared environment red by rspec was
setting the environment for all the test.  This was leading to
unpredictable behavior.

This fix this problem by setting the environment variables before each
test at rspec run time.

commit_message:
Fix leaking environment variables in tests

In rspec provider tests the environment variables are used to
authenticate the calls.  The environment was set in a shared example.
The problem is that rspec read all those environment variables when it
compile the tests.  Then the last shared environment red by rspec was
setting the environment for all the test.  This was leading to
unpredictable behavior.

This fix this problem by setting the environment variables before each
test at rspec run time.

Change-Id: I28c952273d6f981c953cb3e2c960a98609ece263
Closes-Bug: 1482243

commit_message:
Get rid of ConfigParser code in ProviderConfiguration

We may be unable to get rid of this code, but at least we can
make it slimmer and more oslo_config friendly.

This patch also fixes an issue where plain ConfigParser cannot
handle config options with the same name under same section.

Related-bug: #1492069

Change-Id: I596613eb7b2fc3e894a3c1cc7b7cb24d7137cbc5

I've asked Thomas Herve to provide feedback - IIRC the omission of these interfaces was a deliberate design decision when implementing OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup - hopefully therve may have suggestions of how we solve the problem reported without breaking the ASG->LB decoupling he worked hard to establish."}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2015-04-07 10:23:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

As added on the bug:

First, I don't think this was ever meant to work this way, so I don't believe it's a kilo potential bug.

Then, the patch introduces a new attribute on AutoScalingGroup and a weird "allow_non_lbs" flag, which makes me think that it's more about generic signaling between resources than that specific resource type.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-04-07 10:34:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I wonder if we're missing an opportunity to make this interface more generic.

If we landed https://review.openstack.org/#/c/143496/, then the ASG adjustment becomes a signal sent to the ASG resource.

We could then establish a "cascade_signal", or "forward_signal" property or similar, which just forwards the signal to another resource after we finish handling it.  This could even be part of the base SignalResponder implementation, so the same pattern could be applied to all signal-handling resources.

If we combined that with a base resource.Resource handle_signal implementation which simply re-resolved the resource properties when the resource is signalled, I think we might be able to solve this problem in a cleaner and more generic way, without introducing the LB->ASG coupling we have here - which would seem to make sense since what the bug describes is a need for a generic signal/notification/update mechanism, not anything really LB specific.'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-04-07 17:27:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Thomas, wanted to clarify the "weird" allow_non_lbs flag.

The problem is that the function that updates lbs assumes these are the lb resources that Heat knows about. The idea is that with this flag you can also notify custom load balancers, which are nothing more than a regular instance that runs a load balancer such as haproxy.

It's true that you can abuse this and get update notifications sent to any resources that are not load balancers. Maybe changing the property from "load_balancer_names" to something more generic, such as "dependent_resource_names" gives it a better feel?

Note that my initial proposal to fix the bug was to trigger a full update when the ASG resizes. This was turned down by Angus and Steve, so I crafted this limited update solution to solve my problem.'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-04-07 17:46:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Steven,

I'm not sure your proposed patch affects what I'm proposing here, I think even after switching to signals for resizing we still need a way to notify interested resources.

Here is where maybe my big picture understanding is limited. You mention a "cascading signal" sent to other resources, but basically what we need is for those resources to update themselves, not to receive a signal. I can have a resource that is not a signal responder I still need it to update so that any get_attr functions called on the ASG are re-evaluated after the ASG has resized.

Or are you thinking in adding some sort of update signal that all resources can respond to?'}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2015-04-07 19:04:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> The problem is that the function that updates lbs assumes
> these are the lb resources that Heat knows about. The idea 
> is that with this flag you can also notify custom load 
> balancers, which are nothing more than a regular instance 
> that runs a load balancer such as haproxy.
> 
> It's true that you can abuse this and get update 
> notifications sent to any resources that are not load 
> balancers. Maybe changing the property from 
> "load_balancer_names" to something more generic, such as 
> "dependent_resource_names" gives it a better feel?

That's exactly what I meant. And I think it also means that this problem is not specific to autoscaling groups, but rather a generic problem of update notifications between resources. I suspect for example that you'd have the same problem if you used a ResourceGroup instead of an AutoScalingGroup.

In such, it deserves a proper specification with careful thinking. I believe there are 2 options: detect the notification automatically, or declare dependence in the template. As it seems that we have that dependency tree, I would hope that automatic way would work, but I didn't try to look at the implementation details.

Regarding the original bug, while your patch allows updating the metadata, there is no notification for the server, unless you poll the metadata server. It'd be cool to have a solution for that too.'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-04-07 19:22:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> I suspect for example that you'd have the same problem if you used a ResourceGroup instead of an AutoScalingGroup

No, the ResourceGroup works great, actually. The problem is with resources that can update outside of the regular update procedure. The ASG updates as a result of the signal handler of the scale policy calling update, so there is no real stack-wide update. The resource group, on the other side, can only update within the context of a regular update, so everything works. At least that is what I observed in my tests. So I think this is a problem for the ASG only."}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2015-04-07 19:41:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

OK, great. So if we can turn that signaling into something that looks like a regular update, then we get the proper behavior without having to do anything in the template. I think we should try that.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-04-08 12:48:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> what we need is for those resources to update themselves, not to receive a signal.

Yeah, I'm saying that receiving a signal is one possible way of sending such an "asynchronous" (e.g not triggered via stack-update) notification of required update to a resource.

> Or are you thinking in adding some sort of update signal that all resources can respond to?

Yeah, have a base-class signal implementation which just does a re-resolving of the input properties.

For your use-case, the logic we already have (which just re-resolves the resource metadata) would probably be enough:

https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/engine/service.py#L1126'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-04-08 18:08:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> For your use-case, the logic we already have (which just re-resolves the resource metadata) would probably be enough:

This updates resource metadata, so it does not solve my use case, which passes the instance list through server metadata. I could expand update_metadata() to include both resource and server metadata I guess, but that seems like a very narrow solution that only applies to my case.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-04-08 20:01:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-2

What Thomas said - we very carefully and deliberately avoided implementing this for native AutoscalingGroups.'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-04-08 20:03:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Yes, after short discussion in the ML, I'm going to redesign this patch, which even if we use it as is has some limitations. Instead I'm going to see if a full update can be triggered."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-22 06:08:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-09-22 06:11:52.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Update load balancers after HOT autoscaling event

This change adds the ability to update load balancers after an
autoscaling event is triggered on the OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup
resource in HOT templates. This feature is currently available only on
the AWS::AutoScaling::AutoScalingGroup and OS::Heat::InstanceGroup
resources.

To implement this feature the following changes have been
made:

- Add "load_balancer_names" property to the OS::Heat::AutoScalingGroup
  resource, similar to "LoadBalancerNames" in InstanceGroup.
- Allow custom load balancer resources to be included in the
  "load_balancer_names" list. This is done so that regular instances
  running HAProxy or similar load balancers can also be updated after
  the ASG resizes. These custom resources are then able to get the
  updated list of instances through a get_attr call.

Closes-Bug: #1437524
Change-Id: Ib11f29e24e11fba93b59e39e5007f1b6c2814ec6

1. trove.py
With HP's blessing I have taken over this change to help push it over the finish line. I have left this commented code in for their convenience to change at a later date. This change should merge without the dependent api change for now.

2. forms.py
I believe the automatic population is true if you are in a workflow. This is a simple dialog and I believe you are required to populate the choice fields. There are other examples of this in other forms in the dashboard.

3. panel.py
Comment 1:
It was decided by the Trove team that adding Database to the title was redundant. For example, the Backups are title is simply Backups. So for consistency we should keep it simply as "Clusters".

Comment 2:
I don't understand this comment. The panel is under the Database submenu in the Project dashboard. Please elaborate if I am misunderstanding something.

4. views.py
I don't believe the logging is necessary in this case because the method doesn't provide critical information and it may even be redundant in this case so I just left it in and provided some protection so the method doesn't fail.

5. db_capability.py

commit_message:
Initial support for database clustering in Horizon

Added a separate panel for clusters.

This panel contains the Clusters Table with table actions to
Launch and Terminate clusters.  There are row actions Add Shard
and Reset Password (and their associated dialogs) that are specific
to MongoDB and Vertica respectively.

The Clusters Details will include the following tabs:
- Overview
- Instances (table of instances belonging to this cluster)

The launch panel has custom fields for MongoDB and Vertica.
The custom fields will be dynamically shown based on the datastore
selected.

Added a db_capability utility to aid in identifying the specific
datastores.

Added network selection dropdown if neutron is enabled.

Co-Authored-By: Sushil Kumar <sushil.kumar3@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Saurabh Surana <saurabh.surana@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Duk Loi <duk@tesora.com>
Co-Authored-By: Anna Shen <ruiyuan.shen@hp.com>
Change-Id: I047f4d37449070adfd0ea66ad010982f35c049aa
Implements: blueprint database-clustering-support

So, while this fix may work, I would rather we verify the patch above fixes this and bug #1496502 and land that instead.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-18 16:46:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Sorry, correction I meant bug #1467573 and https://review.openstack.org/#/c/223581 above'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-18 16:56:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-18 18:09:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I just added a functional test to my series of patches, which I think proves this is fixed via the move to using the normal stack.validate() path in template-validate:

https://review.openstack.org/225263

Let me know if you disagree that it fixes the issue, thanks!'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-09-21 04:43:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Steven hardy: this patch only targets the problem with NoneResource. which will make the template-validate to go thru.

And only worry i have with your patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/223581/ is it trys to do the same as stack-preview though the output of the command differs.
currently if you user trys to run both template-validate and stack-prview, it would really make sure the template is right for stack creation. only gap is NoneResource failure. this patch would be sufficient to fix the issue with NoneResource. while your patches handles the nested tempalte. kindly let me know otherwise. thanks'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-21 06:43:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> only gap is NoneResource failure.

This is not true - there are a bunch of other weird corner cases caused by the code, such as bug #1467573, and of course the fact that we make no attempt whatsoever to validate any nested stacks at all.

Really, this old duplicate code is a historical artefact, from back when we were hacking together something which could validate and create cloudformation templates.  Now, we've got *way* more sophisticated validation built in to the stack.validate() path, and it (IMHO) makes no sense whatsoever to maintain this old buggy an incomplete validation code, when the whole point is to validate that a create will work.  If that's the aim, why wouldn't using the actual code run by create be better and provide more consistent results?!"}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-21 06:46:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> it trys to do the same as stack-preview though the output of the command differs. 

It does the same as stack-create and stack-preview, which makes sense as the aim is to validate that a create will work.

I agree it's unfortunate that there's some duplication between the validate and preview API's, as the user may be forced to make two quite expensive API calls instead of one - that is not something we can fix until the v2 API, so I'm not really sure why we are discussing it here."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-21 07:25:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

>  currently if you user trys to run both template-validate and stack-prview, it would really make sure the template is right for stack creation. 

This is also not true - running template-validate atm doesn't really prove anything about it being right for stack creation beyond some basic syntax checking of the top-level template - as mentioned there's a bunch of cases where template-validate will work, then stack-create (or stack-preview) will fail.

Moving to using the same logic for validate/create/preview means that if you don't care about the preview output, you may no longer have to make two calls to "really make sure" that the template is validated - that is a really bad API pattern IMO and it just proves that the template-validate in it's existing form does not do it's job, because it does not accurately reflect the validation behavior of preview/create.'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-09-21 08:49:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Workflow-1

shardy: Thanks for making things very clear. I'm putting this patch to WIP, until your patches get merged on validate-template. I will make it abandoned after wards."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-22 05:16:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-09-22 05:57:49.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abandoning this change as its taken care by  https://review.openstack.org/223581 (thanks to shardy)'}]

commit_message:
Template-validate fails when resources are swaped with None resource

validate_template() in service.py is trying to validate the
properties mentioned in the template using the Resource plugin
class. This fails as None resource plugin properties are always
empty.

Fix is added to skip the NoneResource validation appropriately.
TemplateResource also made adhere to same logic.

Change-Id: I3e9e0ee69b863c1cadcff78eed822e3c3a75fbf6
Closes-Bug: #1495914

commit_message:
WiP Only get host data for floating ips on DVR routers

First, we should only be interested in setting the host
attributed whet the router is a DVR router (this may need to be
vetted).  Second, we don't need to query all of the ports on the host,
we just need to query the ports that are referenced by the set of
floating ips that we already have.

Don't merge this.  The original patch has not been merged yet.

Signed-off-by: Ryan Moats <rmoats@us.ibm.com>
Closes-bug: #1496974
(cherry picked from commit 3999409b8c07f7cca9a27fd53aa8ca81cfa64028)

Change-Id: I955a10e135bba9011e68ec6b26d27d82ab2d3410

commit_message:
Add a functional test proving OS::Heat::None works with validate

Previously the template-validate logic failed when overriding
resources with OS::Heat::None in the resource_registry, despite
this working fine via create/preview.

Since the fix for bug #1467573 has aligned the template-validate
logic with that of create/preview, this should now work.

Change-Id: Id8d0be57d347e7ef6714477747949bd2dadd470c
Closes-Bug: #1495914

[{'created': '2015-07-30 05:24:06.000000000', 'message': 'Migrate to Kubernetes 1.0.0

Kubernetes version 1.0 was announced at OSCON.  A new Fedora Atomic image
has been built with this version and this series of patches will update
the templates, scripts, documents to work with the new image.  The api
has also been changed from v1beta3 to v1, so the interface between Magnum
and Kubernetes master needs to be updated as well.
This particular patch will bring up a v1.0 cluster with the bay-create
command.

Change-Id: I046931ad491e8b7ee45943852901eac5c3df913e

and Kubernetes master needs to be updated as well.

command.

commit_message:
Migrate to Kubernetes Release 1

Kubernetes Release 1.0 was announced at OSCON

A new Fedora Atomic image has been built with version 1.0.4 and
this series of patches will update the templates, scripts, documents
to work with the new image.

The api has also been changed from v1beta3 to v1 and the beta
api is no longer available, so the interface between Magnum and
Kubernetes master are updated as well in this series of patches.

This particular patch will bring up a V1 cluster with the
bay-create command.  Because the switch to the V1 API requires
all the code changes to be applied at once, this patch pulls
in portion of 3 patches together.  The changes include:

1. devstack plugin downloads the new image.

2. k8s conductor and other code calls the new V1 client and
k8s methods.

3. Configuration for k8s services and docker updated with
new parameters.

4. Minion registration and example code updated to V1.

5. Functional tests updated to V1.

6. Gate test setup points to the new image.

Co-Authored-By: Hongbin Lu <hongbin.lu@huawei.com>

Change-Id: I046931ad491e8b7ee45943852901eac5c3df913e
Partially-Implements: blueprint kubernetes-v1

commit_message:
test_dashboard_basic_ops: handle urllib2 exceptions in check_login_page

The first HTTP request is done by check_login_page.
This patch aims to try the request and handle exceptions to define
why a request would fail, by giving message and http return code.

Change-Id: If38b5d7e9dd47af87d0b678eac0506243361e852

commit_message:
enhance nova list output with new three fields

Nova list to accept a new parameter --maximal.
Using --maximal option we can have three new fields.
These three new files are
flavor-name
availability-zone-list
image-name

Change-Id: Idf55af5999a323996c7e5f1581901ab4a4174eed

commit_message:
Validates baymodel network_driver requests

Instead of allowing any network_driver value to be accepted by
the baymodel API, this patch limits the value to "flannel". As
additional network drivers get merged, the validation will be
expanded.

Co-Authored-By: Dane LeBlanc <leblancd@cisco.com>
Partially-Implements: blueprint extend-baymodel-net-attributes

Change-Id: I62397f30d08d3d684285cdc9d94a6f5b7d509940

There is a problem in upgrades which is making Jenkins fail with the new 245 script, there are 255 records in the fixed_ips table where instance_uuid is None and that wipes out the fixed_ips table so anything testing against those fails.

Tracking that in bug 1306870.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 17.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

There is a periodic task that runs in the network manager that disassociates fixed IPs from instances 10 minutes after the fixed IP is deallocated, so when the new migration deletes those records, it's also removing the fixed IPs so there is nothing left in the pool and we blow up.  The pool size is 255 for the CIDR block size.

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': 'Add DB2 support

General: I've made this one big patch rather than several patches
in a series because the thinking is we're either going to merge
all of the DB2 support together or none of it at all. This also
helps with the 3rd party CI testing so it can just run tests on
this patch until the code is merged. I've outlined the details below
for reviewing the change.

Notes on migration changes/tests:

1. The initial havana migration does not create any foreign keys which
   require the instances.uuid column since it's nullable and DB2 won't
   allow creating a unique constraint over a nullable column. The lack
   of foreign keys has not presented any functional issues. A possible
   solution is a future patch which makes the instances.uuid column
   non-nullable but that presents it's own difficulties and is outside
   the scope of this change.

2. The ibm_db_sa DB URI in test_migrations.conf is non-standard due to
   how it must be formed to work with the IBM DB2 ODBC/CLI driver.

3. TIMEOUT_SCALING_FACTOR is bumped since the scaling factor of 2 wasn't
   keeping up with the tests on an m1.medium instance used for testing.

4. Schemas are used rather than databases for the tests since the
   create/drop of those are significantly faster in DB2.

Other changes:

1. Handle the 'ibm_db_sa' sqlalchemy engine in the modify_indexes
   utility method.

2. Sync commit 8dccc7b "Handle ibm_db_sa DBDuplicateEntry integrity
   errors" from oslo-incubator. This is needed for 3rd party CI to pass
   for DB2 against Tempest negative tests that rely on duplicate entries
   failing and being handled in the DB API layer. This is not a full
   of the oslo db module since:
   (a) that would pull in far more than is needed here
   (b) oslo db hasn't been synced to Nova since July of 2013 so it would
       not be trivial
   (c) Mirantis is already working on syncing oslo db to Nova but it
       will probably be awhile before that lands.

Implements blueprint db2-database
Closes-Bug: #1227321

Change-Id: Ic4224e2545bcdfeb236b071642f9f16d9ee3b99f

'}, {'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': "WIP: Add DB2 support

General: I've made this one big patch rather than several patches
in a series because the thinking is we're either going to merge
all of the DB2 support together or none of it at all. This also
helps with the 3rd party CI testing so it can just run tests on
this patch until the code is merged. I've outlined the details below
for reviewing the change.

Notes on migration changes/tests:

1. The initial havana migration does not create any foreign keys which
   require the instances.uuid column since it's nullable and DB2 won't
   allow creating a unique constraint over a nullable column. To create
   the foreign keys on instances.uuid I've added migration 245 to drop
   any records where instances.uuid == None (and related tables where
   instance_uuid == None, except for fixed_ips - details inline) so we
   can make instances.uuid non-nullable and create a unique constraint
   on instances.uuid, then new migration 246 creates the missing
   instances.uuid related foreign keys for DB2. There was some mailing
   list discussion about making instances.uuid non-nullable and is
   further discussed in the related nova-spec.

2. The ibm_db_sa DB URI in test_migrations.conf is non-standard due to
   how it must be formed to work with the IBM DB2 ODBC/CLI driver.

3. TIMEOUT_SCALING_FACTOR is bumped since the scaling factor of 2 wasn't
   keeping up with the tests on an m1.medium instance used for testing.

4. Schemas are used rather than databases for the tests since the

"}, {'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': "WIP: Add DB2 support

General: I've made this one big patch rather than several patches
in a series because the thinking is we're either going to merge
all of the DB2 support together or none of it at all. This also
helps with the 3rd party CI testing so it can just run tests on
this patch until the code is merged. I've outlined the details below
for reviewing the change.

Notes on migration changes/tests:

1. The initial havana migration does not create any foreign keys which
   require the instances.uuid column since it's nullable and DB2 won't
   allow creating a unique constraint over a nullable column. To create
   the foreign keys on instances.uuid I've added migration 245 to drop
   any records where instances.uuid == None (and related tables where
   instance_uuid == None, except for fixed_ips - details inline) so we
   can make instances.uuid non-nullable and create a unique constraint
   on instances.uuid, then new migration 246 creates the missing
   instances.uuid related foreign keys for DB2. There was some mailing
   list discussion about making instances.uuid non-nullable and is
   further discussed in the related nova-spec.

2. The ibm_db_sa DB URI in test_migrations.conf is non-standard due to
   how it must be formed to work with the IBM DB2 ODBC/CLI driver.

3. TIMEOUT_SCALING_FACTOR is bumped since the scaling factor of 2 wasn't
   keeping up with the tests on an m1.medium instance used for testing.

4. Schemas are used rather than databases for the tests since the
   create/drop of those are significantly faster in DB2.

Implements blueprint db2-database

Change-Id: Ic4224e2545bcdfeb236b071642f9f16d9ee3b99f

3. Schemas are used rather than databases for the tests since the
   create/drop of those are significantly faster in DB2.

4. The 247_nullable_mismatch migration is updated for DB2 because
   making the pci_devices.deleted column nullable=True fails since
   the column is in a UniqueConstraint already (DB2 would require
   it to be in a unique index instead for the column to be nullable).

Implements blueprint db2-database

   DB2.

commit_message:
Add DB2 support

Notes on migration changes/tests:

1. The initial havana migration does not create any foreign keys which
   require the instances.uuid column since it's nullable and DB2 won't
   allow creating a unique constraint over a nullable column. To create
   the foreign keys on instances.uuid, this change depends on commit
   e07a2b2d4be0503ad8dad75daa632be27cf83320 to make instances.uuid
   non-nullable and create a unique constraint on that column. Then
   the new migration here creates the missing instances.uuid
   related foreign keys for DB2.

2. Commit b930fb3a6b0ab8cbe0c19eb3ab8ba33d60d147be changed
   test_migrations.py to use oslo.db's opportunistic test fixture
   which currently only supports sqlite/mysql/postgresql. Unit test
   support for DB2 therefore needs to be added to oslo.db and then
   hooked into nova, but that's targeted for the 2016.1 'M' release
   so is not part of this change.

3. The 247_nullable_mismatch migration is updated for DB2 because
   making the pci_devices.deleted column nullable=True fails since
   the column is in a UniqueConstraint already (DB2 would require
   it to be in a unique index instead for the column to be nullable).
   There is a foreign key involved (created in 246) so for DB2 to
   have the same FKey it requires a UC and that requires the deleted
   column to be non-null, which doesn't work with the SoftDeleteMixin.
   So in this case the schema will diverge for DB2 until we make
   the deleted column non-nullable for all tables.

4. The 252_add_instance_extra_table migration is updated for DB2
   because a foreign key is created between the instance_extra
   table and the instances.uuid column (which is nullable at the
   time) so we have to handle that foreign key constraint creation
   in the 296 migration with the other foreign keys to
   instances.uuid.

5. The 271 migration is updated to add ibm_db_sa the same as
   sqlite and postgresql since it works the same in this case for
   DB2.

6. The API migrations need checks for DB2 to avoid a duplicate index
   SQL0605W error since DB2 implicitly creates an Index when a
   UniqueConstraint is created and will fail if trying to add a
   duplicate index on the same column(s) that are in the UC.

Implements blueprint db2-database

Change-Id: Ic4224e2545bcdfeb236b071642f9f16d9ee3b99f

commit_message:
Use normal API not token/endpoint for image uploads

There is no reason to use keystone token bootstrapping for image
uploads. Glance is a service, and images can be uploaded to it normally
without special shenanigans.

Depends-On: If7b81c4a6746c8a1eb0302c96e045fb0f457d67b
Change-Id: I7092fb10cbe243e091789134263fab081af0c7f4

commit_message:
Move writing of credentials earlier in the process

If something goes wrong after keystone is running with services
registered, but before credentials are written, it's hard to poke at the
existing half-running state because none of the auth information is
recorded.

Write the files right after we're done bootstrapping keystone.

Change-Id: I2f8ae86e17d26ec4defa16e843faa8987d27fac9

commit_message:
Prevent extraneous log messages and stdout prints

while running unit tests using run_tests.sh,
we can see quite an amount of unwanted log
messages and stdout prints as part of
the unit test results on the console.
This basically makes it difficult to go
through the test results and figure whats happening.

This patch fixes the cause for those
extraneous log messages caused due to
a incorrect fixture usage in test_manage.py
and also by mocking sys.stdout at the respective unit tests.

Closes-bug: #1496898
Change-Id: If986691cb3f36ba357a5c0df34b6df7bf2d8ff86

commit_message:
Fixed an HTTP 500 on artifact blob upload

If the HTTP PUT request to upload a binary file to an artifact does not
contain a Content-size header, the length of the binary file should be
detected during the upload.

However, the unset content size variable was leading to an exception as
its value (None) participates in some math operations during the upload.
Setting the value to 0 (same is v2 API) fixes the issue.

Closes-Bug: #1488037
FastTrack

Change-Id: Iadbd97899445b58c2c5bad961bca61cd6ab60d1a

commit_message:
Add documentation for configuring IdP WebSSO

We recently added a new federation call to Keystone that will allow federated
authentication flows for a specific Identity Provider. This commit adds
documentation around configuring httpd modules for the newly added call and
horizon configuration.

Co-Authored-By: Lin Hua Cheng <os.lcheng@gmail.com>

Change-Id: Id334e979c951387b1d70da70fc5d4939a6e7d6a6
related: bp federation-idp-websso
Closes-Bug: 1491910
Related-Bug: 1491916

Needs tests.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-01-22 19:14:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

I don't understand this configuration.  Could the three replicas of a part be on both machines to *do* support replication and those that don't?  Would this be a permanent state, or is it some sort of transient migration?  Rather than having to rediscover this situation each replication pass could these device nodes that don't support replication just be removed from the ring?

Do you have a DiskFile implementation or use case that actually requires this or does it just seem like a good idea from your perspective?  I'm worried about two misconfigurations that could lead to an confusing runtime state:

1) You've got stock DiskFile setup but you're trying to move replication networks.  When your replication daemons get 405's it just quietly backlist misconfigured nodes instead of raising an error or warning.

2) You've got some nodes configured with this unknown DiskFile that participates in the ring of a replication configured storage policy that is somehow able to stay in sync by some unknown mechanism that doesn't require REPLICATION requests - but then one of those magical nodes has a network hiccup and a handoff (regular replicated DiskFile) ends up receiving the object where it doesn't belong - how would it ever push out that part to non-replicated DiskFile if it can't send a pre-flight REPLICATION request?

Either way this needs tests, but you may need to either provide some more details on how it would ever be reasonable for a mixed DiskFile deployment to behave this way (reference alternative DiskFile that we could install on a swift-all-in-one and test would be ideal) - or barring that maybe a spec to describe the use-case where this would be *required*.  Even if it seems shady in the common case if there's really a use-case where this is the best solution we may be willing to maintain it.

Generally I've stated before that what upstream swift is lacking here is a daemon plugin framework, so people can do this sort of stuff without having to get support to maintain it upstream.

e.g.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/56310/
https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1xzp2RYPAYGRsdj4zanptune-UO2kM6Lu-Oar--slYdg/edit?usp=sharing"}, {'account_id': 8542, 'date': '2015-01-27 09:21:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the review Clay. Here is a snippet from my SAIO remakerings script.

swift-ring-builder object.builder create 10 3 1
swift-ring-builder object.builder add r1z1-127.0.0.1:6010/sdb1 1
swift-ring-builder object.builder add r1z2-127.0.0.1:6020/sdb2 1
swift-ring-builder object.builder add r1z3-127.0.0.1:6030/sdb3 1
swift-ring-builder object.builder add r1z4-127.0.0.1:6040/sdb4 1
swift-ring-builder object.builder add r2z1-127.0.0.1:6050/test 1
swift-ring-builder object.builder rebalance

I have an object server at 127.0.0.1:6050/test which has Swiftonfile (SOF) DiskFile implementation with this patch (https://review.openstack.org/148490). This object server is in region 2. When an object is PUT, two replicas are stored in region 1 distributed among four Swift nodes. The third replica always goes to region 2 which has SOF object server running. This object server has a GlusterFS (could be any posix FS, like GPFS) distributed volume mounted (as device "test"). This volume internally maintains replicas in it's own storage cluster. This volume gives access to objects (the third replica) over filesystem interface. 

One can also have this on a per policy basis, not just cluster wide. For example, a policy may be named as "backup-to-FS-cluster" or "need-fs-access" where one replica is always placed in other region. Example:

swift-ring-builder object.builder create 10 3 1
swift-ring-builder object.builder add r1z1-127.0.0.1:6010/sdb1 1
swift-ring-builder object.builder add r1z2-127.0.0.1:6020/sdb2 1
swift-ring-builder object.builder add r1z3-127.0.0.1:6030/sdb3 1
swift-ring-builder object.builder add r1z4-127.0.0.1:6040/sdb4 1
swift-ring-builder object.builder rebalance
swift-ring-builder object-1.builder create 10 3 1
swift-ring-builder object-1.builder add r1z1-127.0.0.1:6010/sdb1 1
swift-ring-builder object-1.builder add r1z2-127.0.0.1:6020/sdb2 1
swift-ring-builder object-1.builder add r1z3-127.0.0.1:6030/sdb3 1
swift-ring-builder object-1.builder add r1z4-127.0.0.1:6040/sdb4 1
swift-ring-builder object-1.builder add r2z1-127.0.0.1:6050/test 1
swift-ring-builder object-1.builder rebalance

What is the use of such a setup ?
* It allows to keep a backup or alternative copy of every object PUT in GlusterFS volume where objects can be accessed as files over filesystem interface. This volume can also be mounted over NFS or SMB. The volume provides HA in it's own cluster with internal replicas that are in sync.
* When you set read_affinity in proxy to region 1, all GET requests will be served only from Swift cluster which contains two replicas. The third replica will be for internal use over filesystem interface.

This change does log before black listing the node. 501/405 is very specific status code. In a cluster with only stock DiskFile, I don't see any possible way for any object server to return 501/405 as response for REPLICATE request. Hence, in a stock DiskFile only cluster, this change would have absolutely no effect.

Before this change, for any return status which was not HTTP_OK on REPLICATE request, it would get logged and that node gets skipped, only to be recontacted while processing next job. For nodes that return 501/405, this change only postpones the recontact operation until next replicator pass. IMO, this isn't as "intrusive" change as it seems. Without this change, the replicator will continue to contact such nodes even though there is no way for such nodes to handle REPLICATE request. Here are some other DiskFile backends that do not impliment REPLICATE:

https://github.com/stackforge/swift-ceph-backend/blob/master/swift_ceph_backend/rados_server.py#L97-L102

https://github.com/scality/ScalitySproxydSwift/blob/master/swift_scality_backend/server.py#L96-L101

You also brought up a good point about what would happen if all non-Swift-DiskFile nodes in "region 2" experience network partition and a handoff (swift-diskfile) in "region 1" gets the object ? Object replicator on that node cannot sync it to node in region 2, regardless of this change is present or not. So that's a different problem to solve. 

P.S: The daemon plugin framework idea is pretty cool. Thanks for pointing to those links.'}, {'account_id': 8542, 'date': '2015-01-27 11:56:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 8542, 'date': '2015-01-27 12:16:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Skip nodes that does not support REPLICATE verb

Alternative DiskFile backend implementations may not support or
implement REPLICATE verb. This change allows object replicator to
recognize such object servers and "black list" them and not send
further REPLICATE requests. This "black list" is cleared at
beginning of every replicator pass. Hence, each object server that
does not support REPLICATE verb will at the most be contacted once per
pass.

This change assumes that DiskFile implementations return
HTTPNotImplemented (501).

Change-Id: I267808be88a025aaa8ce05ba63c15169ac18df9e
Signed-off-by: Prashanth Pai <ppai@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Fixed non-owner write-access to artifacts

There was no check for write-access priviledges during all the
mutating operations with artifacts (updates, patches, deletes,
actiovations etc), so any user who has an access to an artifact could
modify it. Because of this, non-owners could modify public artifacts
which was a major security issue.

Now this is addressed and an appropriate set of tests added to
prevent possible regressions.

FastTrack
Change-Id: I2f4c2d70b74ae39ababed2ba9b97559ef5ea6d6c
Closes-bug: #1489902

I've been looking lately in similar issues including this one (just forgot to assign it to myself).

1) My major question is if we even need this test test_killed_monitor_respawns() as it totally copies https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/tests/functional/agent/linux/test_async_process.py#L62 and I don't think it adds any additional value in testing. I would vote to remove the test as a whole.

2) If we decide to keep the test and fix racy behavior - we should get rid of calling private method _kill_process() as it's intended to be used from class only, otherwise it introduces another race - see https://review.openstack.org/223160

3) sleep() is not a synchronization mechanism - especially not with hardcoded values, it just can decrease race occurrence rate but won't solve it. We should use active waiting for output."}, {'account_id': 6788, 'date': '2015-09-17 10:47:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
tests: don't validate respawn as part of ovsdb monitor functional test

It's already validated by AsyncProcess functional test suite. Instead,
just validate that the monitor generates the initial output, as
expected.

The test is still useful to validate that rootwrap filter works, so
not removing it completely.

Change-Id: I320edaaa2b210e4b34678c60deb31c4875eea298
Closes-Bug: #1495937

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-17 13:28:43.000000000', 'message': "ovsdb monitor: get rid of custom _read_stdout/_read_stderr methods

Those methods do the same thing as AsyncProcess counterparts, just with logging
the received output. It's better to move the logging into AsyncProcess and
control it with __init__ arguments.

This allows us to get rid of some duplicate tests for ovsdb monitor.

Change-Id: Ic20ded27ba09afdd73e4d96c47469c2d7b4d4db5
Related-Bug: #1495937

commit_message:
ovsdb monitor: get rid of custom _read_stdout/_read_stderr methods

Those methods do the same thing as AsyncProcess counterparts, just
with logging the received output. It's better to move the logging into
AsyncProcess and control it with __init__ arguments.

This allows us to get rid of some duplicate tests for ovsdb monitor.

Change-Id: Ic20ded27ba09afdd73e4d96c47469c2d7b4d4db5
Related-Bug: #1495937

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-02 16:03:21.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] Remove unnecessary tasks in neutron_db_setup.yml

Doing the initial check for existing migrations is pointless -- we can
just run the same DB upgrade tasks irrespective of whether or not we've
already run an upgrade.  Note that this change does replace
neutron_db_revision user variable with neutron_db_expand_revision and
neutron_db_contract_revision since specifying just neutron_db_revision
isn't optimal when we have two branches and can run migrations on each
branch individually.

If there is no value in allowing the DB revision to be specified,
please let me know and I'll just hardcode to head.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1486593
Change-Id: Ie0c5cb5abff61d11b7a9278de6771fa008b69218

"}, {'created': '2015-09-10 10:20:05.000000000', 'message': "More changes to neutron db migrations

This change does the following:

1. Adds user variables and neutron_db_expand_revision and
   neutron_db_contract_revision to replace neutron_db_revision (this is
   necessary since we now have two alembic branches, not one)
2. Runs the initial neutron-db-manage current without grep'ing so we
   can fail if that does not return an exit code of 0 (this is safer,
   as previously an exit code of 1 would go undetected due to the piped
   grep)
3. Updates the grep on the stdout from above to be more precise; neutron
   revision IDs seem to have a lenght ranging from 4 to 12
4. Changes the initial db sync to just doing --expand, which can be
   done whether or not migrations have previously run (this also
   removes the hard-coded reference to 'heads', which may have had
   unintended side-effects if someone specified a different revision)
5. Changes all neutron-db-manage upgrade tasks to use the specified
   revision

If there is no value in allowing the DB revision to be specified,
please let me know and I'll just hardcode to head instead.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1486593
Change-Id: Ie0c5cb5abff61d11b7a9278de6771fa008b69218

"}, {'created': '2015-09-10 12:00:50.000000000', 'message': "More changes to neutron db migrations

This change does the following:

1. Adds user variables and neutron_db_expand_revision and
   neutron_db_contract_revision to replace neutron_db_revision (this is
   necessary since we now have two alembic branches, not one)
2. Runs the initial neutron-db-manage current without grep'ing so we
   can fail if that does not return an exit code of 0 (this is safer,
   as previously an exit code of 1 would go undetected due to the piped
   grep)
3. Creates a new task to parse the output of the above and sets a fact
   if a match is found (this indicates migrations have previously run)
4. Removes the initial db sync task since this is no longer needed
5. Updates the expand task to use the specified revision and runs it
   regardless of whether or not migrations have already been run
6. Similar to above, contract now uses the specified revision and also
   runs regardless, however guards are in place to only stop/start
   neutron-server on a brownfield deploy (doing this on a greenfield
   deploy will fail since the neutron-server service hasn't been
   fully configured/started)

If there is no value in allowing the DB revision to be specified,
please let me know and I'll just hardcode to head instead.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1486593
Change-Id: Ie0c5cb5abff61d11b7a9278de6771fa008b69218

   regardless of whether or not migrations have already been run
6. Similar to above, contract now uses the specified revision and also
   runs regardless, however guards are in place to only stop/start
   neutron-server on a brownfield deploy (doing this on a greenfield
   deploy will fail since the neutron-server service hasn't been
   fully configured/started)

If there is no value in allowing the DB revision to be specified,
please let me know and I'll just hardcode to head instead.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1486593
Change-Id: Ie0c5cb5abff61d11b7a9278de6771fa008b69218
"}, {'created': '2015-09-10 12:13:59.000000000', 'message': "More changes to neutron db migrations

This change does the following:

1. Adds user variables and neutron_db_expand_revision and
   neutron_db_contract_revision to replace neutron_db_revision (this is
   necessary since we now have two alembic branches, not one)
2. Runs the initial neutron-db-manage current without grep'ing so we
   can fail if that does not return an exit code of 0 (this is safer,
   as previously an exit code of 1 would go undetected due to the piped
   grep)
3. Creates a new task to parse the output of the above and sets a fact
   if a match is found (this indicates migrations have previously run)
4. Removes the initial db sync task since this is no longer needed
5. Updates the expand task to use the specified revision and runs it
   regardless of whether or not migrations have already been run
6. Similar to above, contract now uses the specified revision and also
   runs regardless, however guards are in place to only stop/start
   neutron-server on a brownfield deploy (doing this on a greenfield
   deploy will fail since the neutron-server service hasn't been
   fully configured/started)

If there is no value in allowing the DB revision to be specified,
please let me know and I'll just hardcode to head instead.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1486593
Change-Id: Ie0c5cb5abff61d11b7a9278de6771fa008b69218
"}, {'created': '2015-09-11 09:05:24.000000000', 'message': "Add neutron_migrations_facts module

This change does the following:

1. Adds neutron_migrations_facts module, which creates a fact
   with the state of each neutron alembic migration branch
2. Removes the migration check task since this is now handled by the
   neutron_migrations_facts module
3. Adds user variables and neutron_db_expand_revision and
   neutron_db_contract_revision to replace neutron_db_revision (this is
   necessary since we now have two alembic branches, not one)
4. Updates the upgrade tasks to work with a specific revision and only
   executes these tasks if the branch is not on head
5. Updates roles/os_neutron/tasks/main.yml so the init scripts are
   dropped before we handle db syncing, which means we can stop the
   neutron-server on a greenfield deploy

If there is no value in allowing the DB revision to be specified,

commit_message:
Add neutron_migrations_facts module

This change does the following:

1. Adds neutron_migrations_facts module, which creates a fact
   with the state of each neutron alembic migration branch
2. Removes var neutron_db_revision since this is no longer used
3. Removes the migration check task since this is now handled by the
   neutron_migrations_facts module
4. Updates roles/os_neutron/tasks/main.yml so the init scripts are
   dropped before we handle db syncing, which means we can stop the
   neutron-server on a greenfield deploy

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1486593
Change-Id: Ie0c5cb5abff61d11b7a9278de6771fa008b69218

@Joe: (1) tags are definitely documentation and not governance, they will likely move to a separate repository soon. (2) To answer your question "as a deployer and end user why would I care" -- the ops at the Ops Summit were pretty insistent on the need to define such role/kernel/base tags for base orientation on what is the minimal set of projects to implement to cover very basic use cases. This information (or some variant of it) was actually their #1 request in that "what information about projects would be useful to you" session. So they care a lot, and I think Deva's rationale captures why accurately.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-12 16:54:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Do ops want to know what is cloud native and what is in the compute ring? or just care about the compute ring?'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2015-03-12 20:32:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Joe, I believe we'll need more tags than just "compute base ring" and "cloud native" -- for example, "object cloud" for swift, or "bare metal cloud" to describe the set of things that folks probably want for ironic, and so on. 

The ones posted here are just two examples. I'll try to write up the ones I just mentioned soon (maybe tomorrow) and update the review'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-03-16 17:41:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-16 18:08:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

after looking at some more user/ops feedback it sounds like there are really two things people want the base-compute-ring tag for.

  * Having us formally define what the base services are. While this isn't actually very hard to figure out on your own, having a formal definition just makes things easier.
  *  Using it as a proxy for quality. There seems to be a lot of interesting in making sure the foundation services are robust and high quality so we can build new services, and end user workloads on a good foundation. This also means companies can tell their developers 'work on the base services, as we want them to be really robust.' 


So I am not sure the current proposal fits those two cases very well."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-17 20:41:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-03-18 02:04:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(7 comments)

Thanks for submitting this, I think it's a great way to discuss in a concrete way what sort of tags the TC should be creating.

That said, I think these are prime examples of the kinds of tags that should never be created.

These are examples of using tags as bad documentation. I say they're terrible as documentation because they each contain only 1 bit of entropy, and the world is much more complicated than that. I myself am pretty familiar what every project in OpenStack is for, yet even given that knowledge, the tag names, the long-form tag descriptions and the list of projects that each would be applied to, I can't work out for sure what most of these mean. If the intended audience is folks with less knowledge of OpenStack arcana than us (and the application of tags is delegated to different groups that don't necessarily have a shared understanding of their meaning!), I don't see how they have any chance.

As a hypothetical example, let's take a newbie operator who is trying to figure out whether they need to install, say, Trove. Here's the kind of thing some introductory documentation might say:

"Trove is a service for providing on-demand, automated provisioning of databases. Databases provisioned by Trove run on VMs allocated with Nova and configured via Heat."

and the role tags would say:

  [role:cloud-native-application]

I submit that the former takes barely longer to read and tells our hypothetical user everything he or she needs to know: that Trove provides a database service, and that they'll also need to have (not necessarily user-facing) Nova and Heat services deployed too in order to use it. The latter, on the other hand, tells them nothing at all, and may even be actively misleading.


In my opinion, tags should represent aspirations that the TC has for projects. As such, the individual criteria we previously used in incubation and graduation reviews are the obvious first candidates for new tags. That will increase the granularity of the TC's communication about the state of projects from the previous Out/Incubated/Integrated to publicly share the progress on individual criteria, which was the point of the tagging system. The TC can use these tags to guide projects as they move toward e.g. trademark eligibility.

BTW one advantage of these sorts of tags is that the set of possible values are generally {Yes, Not yet}, rather than {Yes, No}. That's helpful because in the former case, "Not yet" and "Not evaluated yet" map to the same value. For example, if a user wants to know whether a service has a stable API, then the 'stable-api' tag is helpful because the answers "Not yet" and "Not evaluated yet" both map to "You're on your own" and therefore can both be represented by the lack of a tag. However, if a user wants to know if a particular service has a user interface role, then there had better be a centralised group evaluating every new project promptly for 'role:user-interface' because the answers "No" and "What're tags?" have completely different meanings (assuming, for a moment, we don't accept that _all_ values of this tag mean "read the docs") that are not distinguishable when the tag is simply not applied.


Finally, I have a strong fear that all tags we create will be interpreted as aspirational, even if they are intended only to be informational. In particular, I've heard many alarming suggestions about how people might interpret role:base-compute-group (including that the TC need pay no further attention to projects that aren't in it). It seems bound to turn into a more-toxic version of the same old "Core" confusion.

If we're lacking the kind of documentation that I wrote above for Trove (though I'm not sure we are), then by all means let's write it. If it's not together in one place then let's aggregate it. If adopters need better information about what kinds of shapes their OpenStack clouds can take, then let's provide a place (Superuser?) where our community, in all their diversity, can contribute case studies. But let's keep these ineffectual single-bit documentation attempts out of the tags, where they're easily misinterpreted and/or taken as a value judgement, and leave them for the more detailed, nuanced documentation that everybody is going to have to read anyway.

I would also note that we'll achieve a stable OpenStack *not* by incentivising companies to contribute to services that some authority has designated as important, but rather by finding a way to incentivise more of them to contribute more to bug-fixing, testing and design improvements in addition to their pet features and back-ends. In any case, if a developer wants to know which projects to work on they can just ask their boss which ones their customers are using - the result will automatically reflect the priorities of the community, and IMHO the idea that the TC (or a self-appointed clique enabled by the TC, as proposed here) needs to step in and redirect priorities (in favour of what I assume is already the largest group of contributors anyway) is as inappropriate as it is redundant.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-03-20 20:01:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I agree with Zane's assessment. We should use complete sentences to describe what things are for and how they're used. We can do that with use cases, example deployment scenarios, index cross-references in a product guide, or just simple prose. But having to manage a set of tags to group projects feels like the wrong approach."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-04-02 14:22:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think the role: tags as proposed conflate multiple concepts into one, and we might want to use different families for those.

Tags are created to provide information about projects to downstream users of OpenStack. I've been busy lately meeting them in various settings. From these contacts, I think two basic questions emerged, questions that are *not* properly answered currently.

1/ What is the minimal set of projects I should be considering to deliver base Compute IaaS functionality ? The full picture is scary, and it's non-trivial to determine what is necessary from what is optional.

2/ I know Swift is Object Storage, but what are the other projects helping in the same problem space (storage) ?

To answer those two questions, I suggest we move toward defining two families of tags. The "base:*" tags would describe starter kits of OpenStack projects. The "theme:*" tags would describe the area a given project covers.

Example: "base:compute" tag would describe the very minimal set of projects necessary to achieve non-ephemeral compute IaaS. Also known as "Nova and what Nova requires".

Example: "theme:storage" would be applied to Swift, Cinder, Manila. "theme:user-interface" would let you find UI bits.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-08-21 12:30:58.000000000', 'content': 'Topic changed from add-role-tags to formal-vote'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2015-09-22 03:33:15.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
WIP - add some tags describing roles

This is a rough initial draft, adding four new tags along two axis.
I fully expect that it will be met with some disagreement, and would
like a discussion around both what is wrong and what is missing from
this proposal.

Covering some of the existing service projects' intended usage,
these two tags describe where in the stack an OpenStack service
fits:
- role:base-compute-ring
- role:cloud-native-application

Covering the intended consumer of user-facing projects, these two tags
describe whether the project targets cloud operators or cloud
application developers.
- role:user-interface
- role:operator-interface

Neither of the above axis are completely covered in the current
proposal. Eg, none of these tags would apply to swift, ironic, or
devstack.

Change-Id: I68955d0122884d3d351193347ca8d61410c232cb

[{'created': '2015-09-18 00:13:41.000000000', 'message': 'Only write to template files if template data changes

Currently the template data is assigned to the files dict regardless
of whether the data has changed or not.

This has no consequence on Liberty, but the files dict in Kilo
and Juno is a sqlalchemy MutableDict so these assignments are triggering
updates to the raw_template table. These updates are even triggered for
calls to heat resource-list. With large raw_template records this can make
heat unusable.

Therefore this fix is presented here as having no effect (and being
harmless) to git master, but high priority backports for Kilo and Juno.

Change-Id: Ibb714a9c5dc9f6879ff108419127da985a57897b
Closes-Bug: #1494108
'}]
commit_message:
Only write to template files if template data changes

Currently the template data is assigned to the files dict regardless
of whether the data has changed or not.

This has no consequence on Liberty, but the files dict in Kilo
and Juno is a sqlalchemy MutableDict so these assignments are triggering
updates to the raw_template table. These updates are even triggered for
calls to heat resource-list. With large raw_template records this can make
heat unusable.

Therefore this fix is presented here as having no effect (and being
harmless) to git master, but high priority backports for Kilo and Juno.

Change-Id: Ibb714a9c5dc9f6879ff108419127da985a57897b
Closes-Bug: #1494108

this is a great cleanup - but man... what I web.  Here's some notes I took while trying to track down all the movement:

     * listdir extracted from _get_ondisk_file and moved into open
     * _get_ondisk_file parameterized files (results of listdir)
     * DiskFile and ECDiskFile already implement _get_ondisk_file (but now with
       less code!)
     * _get_ondisk_file in both cases was and continues to wrap
       manager.get_ondisk_files (EC includes frag_index=self._frag_index)
         ... and is only called from open
     * manager.get_ondisk_files used to return a tuple - now it returns a dict
         ... which _get_ondisk_file passes out
         ... and appears to be the only accessor of this interface
         ... so open got updated to eat it (and some tests that hit
             _get_ondisk_files directly)


I think we could go even further to make the most out of the dict return

[{'created': '2015-09-11 16:59:17.000000000', 'message': 'diskfile: make get_ondisk_files return a dict

get_ondisk_files gathers a dict with more info than just the set
of data, ts and/or meta files, but only returns the
set of files to the DiskFile class. The other info
in the dict may be useful policy specific  implementations, so
return the whole dict.

Also, refactor _get_ondisk_file to move duplicated code into the
BaseDiskFile open() method.

Change-Id: I7a17d26b7ed7f7c593f577332937793419c03cfa

commit_message:
diskfile: make get_ondisk_files return a dict

get_ondisk_files gathers a dict with more info than just the set
of data, ts and/or meta files, but only returns the
set of files to the DiskFile class. The other info
in the dict may be useful policy specific implementations, so
return the whole dict.

Also, refactor _get_ondisk_file to move duplicated code into the
BaseDiskFile open() method.

Change-Id: I7a17d26b7ed7f7c593f577332937793419c03cfa
Co-Authored-By: Paul Luse <paul.e.luse@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Clay Gerrard <clay.gerrard@gmail.com>

Hey Mike, thanks for taking a look at it. The latest patch fixes that log error... I'm not sure how exactly that happened (or why it didn't blow up on my test machine the last time I rearranged things and introduced it...) but it should be fine now again.

The virtual size thing is kind of a pain right now.. I followed the same caching model John implemented in the Solidfire driver where we use the image virtual size, viewable via qemu-img info, to make the cached volume as small as possible so it can be used with any incoming requests to avoid having to shrink the volume. This requires that an image have a property on it called 'virtual_size' which is that value. You will have to set it on an image with something like: "glance image-update --property virtual_size='1.0' cirros-0.3.4-x86_64-uec"

The good news is that glance appears to be moving in a direction to be able to set 'virtual_size' in the image metadata for us. If you use the v2 glance api all images will have the field. Unfortunately right now it appears that it is only set when using a certain flow to create the image... Tomoki pointed me to http://www.sebastien-han.fr/blog/2015/05/11/openstack-glance-a-first-glimpse-at-image-conversion/ which shows steps to get an image with the size automatically set.

I will update the commit message to make this more clear, just noticed it isn't actually mentioned....'}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2015-07-29 16:26:41.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 25.'}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2015-07-29 17:43:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 24:

I was doing some error path testing (via fault injection at times) and I hit a few simple issues with LOG messages:

cinder/image/cache.py
    line 184:  missing {'host': host} or similar from the LOG.warning
        harmless - but easy to cleanup.

cinder/volume/manager.py
    line 256 causes the following:

Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/logging/__init__.py", line 851, in emit
    msg = self.format(record)
  File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/oslo_log/handlers.py", line 115, in format
    return logging.StreamHandler.format(self, record)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/logging/__init__.py", line 724, in format
    return fmt.format(record)
  File "/usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/oslo_log/formatters.py", line 236, in format
    return logging.Formatter.format(self, record)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/logging/__init__.py", line 464, in format
    record.message = record.getMessage()
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/logging/__init__.py", line 328, in getMessage
    msg = msg % self.args
TypeError: format requires a mapping
Logged from file manager.py, line 256
> /opt/stack/cinder/cinder/volume/manager.py(257)__init__()
-> self.image_volume_cache = None

    Simple to correct if you add {'host': self.host} instead of self.host to the LOG line.

    Additionally as long as you are in this code it might be nice to put a message for the enabled case:
LOG.debug('Image-volume cache enabled for host %(host)s',{'host': self.host})'}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2015-07-31 21:51:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 27.'}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2015-07-31 21:51:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 26:

I've noticed something weird with the v2 glance api where it does not send image properties back when we do a GET on the image.... I'm looking into whether this is something Cinder is doing wrong or Glance, but from the api docs http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-image-v2.html#getImage-v2 it looks like it should be included in the response :(

This means that as-is if using the v2 Glance API an image will have to be either raw or have the actual virtual_size set on it (not just a property on the image)."}, {'account_id': 10327, 'date': '2015-08-13 02:26:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 35:

Might need some more info on how to test/run this.  I created a tenant and user and added to default section of conf:

cinder_internal_tenant_project_id = 7a17a6fb37864348ab2db522870f6b03
cinder_internal_tenant_user_id = 5cd2872910894cca92ac019a0d466c05

I also added the following in the driver section:
image_volume_cache_enabled=True
image_volume_cache_max_size_gb=0
image_volume_cache_max_count=0

So far so good... but then when trying to create volume from image I get:
INFO cinder.image.cache [req-ee548891-ecd4-4c3c-b6c2-0bcfe2f2ef90 None] Unable to use ImageVolumeCache because image 5784e30f-64ee-4481-ab82-02eea526716a is not accessible by internal tenant.

Which I don't quite get as it's a public image. It also makes me interested in what I wanted to test in the first place which is how it deals with access to images?  In other words, if a tenant creates an image and marks it private; how does the internal "special" tenant get access?  Is it kind of risky to have an uber tenant that is actually shared among tenants and accesses *all* images?

Also, on a side note; I was thinking of a possible way to get around that pesky virtual_size setting requirement in the image, but that's not really important right now probably.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-19 05:14:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 41: Verified-1

Maybe you should document how to set this up so people can test it?

Here's what I did on my side:
* create internal tenant
keystone tenant-create --name cinderinternal --description "Internal cinder"

Then in my conf file:
cinder_internal_tenant_project_id = 944e8fa23e144622ad4411fdff24de10

[database]
connection = mysql+pymysql://root:solidfire@127.0.0.1/cinder?charset=utf8

[oslo_concurrency]

[solidfire]
san_password = admin
san_login = admin
san_ip = 11.0.0.2
volume_driver = cinder.volume.drivers.solidfire.SolidFireDriver
volume_backend_name = solidfire
image_volume_cache_enabled = True
sf_allow_template_caching = False


First problem:
image_volume_cache_enabled isn't detected/set from the driver section, it has to be in the default section; I'm not sure why:
2015-08-29 16:09:47.974 DEBUG oslo_service.service [req-8ff5722d-f3dc-44fb-911e-458db1cd46d5 None] image_volume_cache_enabled     = False log_opt_values /usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/oslo_config/cfg.py:2225

So I moved it to default section, now at least it's enabled... but the next problem:
