John, appologies for the trouble configuring... I had put together instructions for folks testing this (thingee and hemna both successfully used them so hopefully they are still valid) and apparently forgot to actually post them on the review and not just in IRC once. https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/cinder-generic-image-volume-cache'}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2015-08-29 17:19:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 50:

John, I think the problem you are running into is just that the internal tenant is missing a user id config setting. From the steps you posted you will need to configure cinder_internal_tenant_user_id and cinder_internal_tenant_project_id

For the issue with having to put the config in the default section... i'm not sure whats up with that. For my tests that wasn't the case, maybe something different with the solidfire drivers or how your cinder is configured? 

I define the config options in cinder/volume/driver.py in the volume_opts which afaik should allow for them to be in default or the backend section. Please advise if that is not correct."}, {'account_id': 5997, 'date': '2015-08-30 01:54:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 50: Code-Review-1

So, I was able to test this with Patrick's instructions on the etherpad.   This works just fine for our LeftHand driver, but it doesn't work for our 3PAR drivers.   The problem is related to calling extend on a volume that's in process of being cloned.   This is probably why all of the 3PAR CI failures.   I don't have a solution to fix this for our driver just yet that doesn't involve some painful hacks.  

 Ideally it would be nice to be able to disable this from running against our driver even if an admin tries to enable it.   I guess for L, we'll just update the documentation for our driver that it doesn't work, or submit a follow up patch that looks for the config option being enabled and raise an exception in do_setup(), this will leave our driver marked as not initialized.

Suggestions?"}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2015-08-30 02:20:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 50:

Walt, so is the suggestion that we look for some kind of feature flag in the driver capabilities? Or like we add a driver hook to enable/disable this and override the config option? (which defaults to off anyway, those 3PAR CI failures are unrelated to this change as far as i can tell) Is there a good example of something like that in place for other features I can use as an example to work off of?

FWIW I don't really see it as too bad to leave this as-is and adding documentation that it isn't going to work for some backends... having config settings that when enabled break something is IMO less bad than having config settings that only sometimes actually do what they are intended to do. Either way it doesn't work and probably needs documentation around it. Does that make sense?


I kind of don't like the idea of this not merging because of a quirk in the 3PAR clone volume implementation (which would be broken by a user scripting a cinder create/extend too quickly anyway)...but I'm willing to do whatever you guys need with the code to turn that -1 into a +1 or 2 as long as we can do it before the freeze date :D"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-30 12:59:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 50: Verified-1

Running into a couple of problems, the driver configs not effecting backends is something we should def fix IMO; saying "we'll document that it doesn't work for this driver", also the suggestion that "we just document it doesn't work for this driver" kind of defeats the whole purpose in my opinion.

Anyway, more importantly; because we're implementing this in the taskflow code the way it's done here we don't have the ability to effect driver/backend conf settings.  We need to either load the backend opts into the conf object early and use them (this may cause issues with 'already registered' options later though) and be able to set things like the quotas and enable etc.

The way enable and qutoas are set now as a global can be problematic I think; first there's devices that won't dedupe or compress so they're flat out not going to want this on because of usage, and there are others that might have smaller devices/clusters and won't want to wast space creating images on them (think lower tier price points from SP's).

The other problem I still have is there's no context matching passed in on the clone.  In other words the clone request is passed in, however it's passed in with the context of the "real" tenant, which doesn't have access to volumes owned by the "internal" tenant on the backend.  We should add a param to pass in the internal tenant context object, but regardless this means a number of backends need to do a bit of work to implement this.

Finally, there's something going on in the db side that I haven't looked at or figure out.  But, if folks test this they may notice that "yes" the volume is create (and even the cache volume is created), however there's some nasty stack traces in the logs in some cases (this might be related to issues mentioned above):
http://paste.openstack.org/show/435056/

Some of this we could certainly fix up as part of the bug cleanup phase for Liberty but I'm concerned that there's quite a bit of "unknown" here still.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-08-31 15:54:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 52:

BTW, the context thing is pretty easy to get around actually, we can just read the internal tenant-id from the CONF object.  I still need to figure out what's up with the DB issues though, as it is right now it actually creates 3 cache volumes, and zero entries in the db table."}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2015-08-31 19:29:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 52:

Thanks for trying this again John. So, let me try and tackle these issues point by point. We discussed some of it IRC too.

* The comment about documenting it as not working for some drivers is specific to issues like the 3PAR where it cannot do a clone and then extend immediately. That kind of behavior is, IMO, a design flaw in the VolumeDriver that is atypical of what Cinder expects. I do want this cache to be generic and work for everyone, and have been discussing with Walt how we can make this work for them. My suggestion that we have to document it as not working is concerning the suggestion of allowing a driver to override the configuration. My point being that either we document that 'if you enable this feature it will break for this backend' or we say 'if you enable this feature it will not actually do anything for this backend and the feature wont really be enabled'. Either way, IMO, we are saying 'it doesn't work for this driver'. One just hides the problem transparently and the other upfront sets expectations. Does that make sense? I'm not sure what we've done in the past for this sort of thing so I might be totally off base...

* I totally agree with you about the driver scoped config options. As-is it is working that way for me, the local.conf sample https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/cinder-generic-image-volume-cache shows almost exactly what i'm testing with and it is using backend scoped configs for them. The 3 config options for the cache (enable, size gb, and size count) are defined as volume_opts in cinder/volume/driver.py. These are then read a used by the VolumeManager when it initializes in cinder/volume/manager.py, at that point in time it should definitely have access to the driver/backend config options. The only thing read while in the flow is the internal tenant config items which IMO should *not* be driver/backend scoped. I want to say the config stuff is working as intended... that being said maybe I'm intending it to work wrong ;)

* For the context matching, after our discussion in IRC I understand the issue now. After poking around the code to figure out why it still works just fine as-is I realized that at the points we are doing this the context is elevated. This means that the db.volume_get() call will work the same way with either the internal context or calling context. Now, that being said.. it does seem kind of weird, but I'm a little bit hesitant to change too much of the context vs admin context stuff in the create_volume flow/manager code without a more thorough design review (spec?) to ensure we standardize on how this is supposed to be working. From my point of view though we can adjust this later on transparently to an end-user since the behavior of the cache wouldn't change. It's just how we internally are doing db queries and stuff. Does that sound like a reasonable approach?

* The db issue... I can't repro this :( Do you have any additional info to help me troubleshoot that? (repro steps? cinder.conf/local.conf? What image?) I'm looking into stopping the taskflow retries for failure cases of this. Ideally it should be cleaning up the volumes and maybe trying again without using the cache. At a minimum I think it probably should be cleaning up the volumes. I'll keep playing around with that this afternoon."}, {'account_id': 7198, 'date': '2015-08-31 22:02:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 52: Code-Review-2

Change-Id: If22bbaff89251e4e82a715170a48b4040f95c09f'}, {'created': '2015-07-08 00:28:49.000000000', 'message': "WIP Generic image cache.

Note: Still needs a bunch of tests, but is otherwise mostly of working.

This introduces a new feature for backends to be able to use cached
glance images when creating volumes from images. If enabled, and the
cinder internal tenant is configured, it will create a minimal sized
clone of a volume the first time it is downloaded from glance. A new db
table ‘image_volume_cache’ tracks these volumes, which are owned by the
Cinder internal tenant. The original will then be extended to full size.
Any subsequent requests to create a volume from an image will be able
to do a volume clone from the image-volume cache entry instead of
downloading the image data from glance again.

These image-volumes are host specific, so each backend may end up with
its very own image-volume to do clones from.

The cache is limited in size by number of entries allowed and size in
gb. When creating a new entry if size is needed the last used entries
will be evicted to make room.

In the current implementation the image-volumes will be viewable by a
cloud admin in the volume list, and show up as owned by the Cinder
internal tenant. They can safely be deleted manually by an admin, this
will cause the entry to be removed from the cache. These volumes do not
take any quota from *any* user. They are only limited by the cache size
configuration options.

Cache actions will post notifications to Ceilometer. There are
notifications like ‘image_volume_cache.miss’, ‘image_volume_cache.hit’,
and ‘image_volume_cache.evict’. A change will be required to the
event_definitions.yaml to see them nicely. Until then you only need to
add a new event type 'image_volume_cache.*' and look for the ‘image_id’
and ‘host’ fields.


DocImpact: We probably want some instructions on restrictions of the
cache and how to use it.

Implements: image-volume-cache
Change-Id: If22bbaff89251e4e82a715170a48b4040f95c09f"}, {'created': '2015-07-08 02:14:10.000000000', 'message': "WIP Generic image cache.

Change-Id: If22bbaff89251e4e82a715170a48b4040f95c09f"}, {'created': '2015-07-21 02:42:02.000000000', 'message': "Generic image-volume cache

This introduces a new feature for backends to be able to use cached
glance images when creating volumes from images.

If enabled, and the cinder internal tenant is configured, it will
create a minimal sized clone of a volume the first time it is
downloaded from glance. A new db table ‘image_volume_cache’ tracks
these volumes, which are owned by the Cinder internal tenant. The
original will then be extended to full size. Any subsequent requests to
create a volume from an image will be able to do a volume clone from
the image-volume cache entry instead of downloading the image data from
glance again.

It will also create an entry upon creating an image from a volume right
before uploading the volume to glance.

These image-volumes are host specific, so each backend may end up with
its very own image-volume to do clones from.

The cache is limited in size by number of entries allowed and size in
gb. When creating a new entry if space is needed the last used entries
will be evicted to make room.

In the current implementation the image-volumes will be viewable by a
cloud admin in the volume list, and show up as owned by the Cinder
internal tenant. They can safely be deleted manually by an admin, this
will cause the entry to be removed from the cache. These volumes will
use quota for the internal tenant.

Cache actions will post notifications to Ceilometer. There are
notifications like ‘image_volume_cache.miss’, ‘image_volume_cache.hit’,
and ‘image_volume_cache.evict’. A change will be required to the
event_definitions.yaml to see them nicely. Until then you only need to
add a new event type 'image_volume_cache.*' and look for the ‘image_id’
and ‘host’ fields.

DocImpact: We probably want some instructions on restrictions of the
cache and how to use it. The three new config options should also be
documented somewhere: ‘image_volume_cache_enabled’,
’image_volume_cache_max_size_gb’, ‘image_volume_cache_max_size_count’

This introduces a new feature for backends to be able to use cached
glance images when creating volumes from images.

If enabled, and the cinder internal tenant is configured, it will
create a minimal sized clone of a volume the first time it is
downloaded from glance. A new db table ‘image_volume_cache’ tracks
these volumes, which are owned by the Cinder internal tenant. The
original will then be extended to full size. Any subsequent requests to
create a volume from an image will be able to do a volume clone from
the image-volume cache entry instead of downloading the image data from
glance again.

This functionality requires an image to have its ‘virtual_size’ set in
its Glance metadata. With the v2 glance API certain workflows to create
images will automatically set this, but for others it will require a
manual step to set the ‘virtual_size’ property on the image.

Future changes to Glance and Cinder can make this more automated to
set the virtual size any chance we can. For example when creating a
volume from image though the default driver implementation in Cinder
we actually get the virtual size from a qemu-img command. We could
potentially set it on the image automatically for a user. This is
however something to be done on top of the initial cache functionality
and would be added later on in another change.

In the future we could create an entry upon creating an image from a
volume right before uploading the volume to glance. This version
however does not aim to do more than add the initial framework and
help with subsequent image downloads. There are certainly more
improvements that can be done over time on top of this.

These image-volumes are host specific, so each backend may end up with
its very own image-volume to do clones from.

The cache is limited in size by number of entries allowed and size in
gb. When creating a new entry if space is needed the last used entries
will be evicted to make room.

In the current implementation the image-volumes will be viewable by a
cloud admin in the volume list, and show up as owned by the Cinder
internal tenant. They can safely be deleted manually by an admin, this
will cause the entry to be removed from the cache. These volumes will
use quota for the internal tenant.

Cache actions will post notifications to Ceilometer. There are

and ‘image_volume_cache.evict’. A change will be required to the
event_definitions.yaml to see them nicely. Until then you only need to

and ‘host’ fields.

cache and how to use it. The three new config options should also be
documented somewhere: ‘image_volume_cache_enabled’,
’image_volume_cache_max_size_gb’, ‘image_volume_cache_max_size_count’

This introduces a new feature for backends to be able to use cached
glance images when creating volumes from images.

If enabled, and the cinder internal tenant is configured, it will
create a minimal sized clone of a volume the first time it is
downloaded from glance. A new db table ‘image_volume_cache’ tracks
these volumes, which are owned by the Cinder internal tenant. The
original will then be extended to full size. Any subsequent requests to
create a volume from an image will be able to do a volume clone from
the image-volume cache entry instead of downloading the image data from
glance again.

This functionality requires an image to have its ‘virtual_size’ set in
its Glance metadata. With the v2 glance API certain workflows to create
images will automatically set this, but for others it will require a
manual step to set the ‘virtual_size’ property on the image.

Future changes to Glance and Cinder can make this more automated to
set the virtual size any chance we can. For example when creating a
volume from image though the default driver implementation in Cinder
we actually get the virtual size from a qemu-img command. We could
potentially set it on the image automatically for a user. This is
however something to be done on top of the initial cache functionality
and would be added later on in another change.

In the future we could create an entry upon creating an image from a
volume right before uploading the volume to glance. This version
however does not aim to do more than add the initial framework and
help with subsequent image downloads. There are certainly more
improvements that can be done over time on top of this.

These image-volumes are host specific, so each backend may end up with
its very own image-volume to do clones from.

The cache is limited in size by number of entries allowed and size in
gb. When creating a new entry if space is needed the last used entries
will be evicted to make room.

In the current implementation the image-volumes will be viewable by a
cloud admin in the volume list, and show up as owned by the Cinder
internal tenant. They can safely be deleted manually by an admin, this
will cause the entry to be removed from the cache. These volumes will
use quota for the internal tenant.

Cache actions will post notifications to Ceilometer. There are
notifications like ‘image_volume_cache.miss’, ‘image_volume_cache.hit’,
and ‘image_volume_cache.evict’. A change will be required to the
event_definitions.yaml to see them nicely. Until then you only need to
add a new event type 'image_volume_cache.*' and look for the ‘image_id’
and ‘host’ fields.

DocImpact: We probably want some instructions on restrictions of the
cache and how to use it. The three new config options should also be
documented somewhere: ‘image_volume_cache_enabled’,
’image_volume_cache_max_size_gb’, ‘image_volume_cache_max_size_count’

Implements: image-volume-cache
Change-Id: If22bbaff89251e4e82a715170a48b4040f95c09f

set the virtual size any chance we can. For example when creating a
volume from image though the default driver implementation in Cinder
we actually get the virtual size from a qemu-img command. We could
potentially set it on the image automatically for a user. This is
however something to be done on top of the initial cache functionality
and would be added later on in another change.

In the future we could create an entry upon creating an image from a
volume right before uploading the volume to glance. This version
however does not aim to do more than add the initial framework and
help with subsequent image downloads. There are certainly more
improvements that can be done over time on top of this.

These image-volumes are host specific, so each backend may end up with
its very own image-volume to do clones from.

The cache is limited in size by number of entries allowed and size in
gb. When creating a new entry if space is needed the last used entries
will be evicted to make room.

In the current implementation the image-volumes will be viewable by a
cloud admin in the volume list, and show up as owned by the Cinder
internal tenant. They can safely be deleted manually by an admin, this
will cause the entry to be removed from the cache. These volumes will
use quota for the internal tenant.

Cache actions will post notifications to Ceilometer. There are
notifications like ‘image_volume_cache.miss’, ‘image_volume_cache.hit’,
and ‘image_volume_cache.evict’. A change will be required to the
event_definitions.yaml to see them nicely. Until then you only need to
add a new event type 'image_volume_cache.*' and look for the ‘image_id’
and ‘host’ fields.

DocImpact: We probably want some instructions on restrictions of the
cache and how to use it. The three new config options should also be
documented somewhere: ‘image_volume_cache_enabled’,
’image_volume_cache_max_size_gb’, ‘image_volume_cache_max_size_count’

commit_message:
Generic image-volume cache

This introduces a new feature for backends to be able to use cached
glance images when creating volumes from images.

If enabled, and the cinder internal tenant is configured, it will
create a minimal sized clone of a volume the first time it is
downloaded from glance. A new db table ‘image_volume_cache’ tracks
these volumes, which are owned by the Cinder internal tenant. The
original will then be extended to full size. Any subsequent requests to
create a volume from an image will be able to do a volume clone from
the image-volume cache entry instead of downloading the image data from
glance again.

In the future we could create an entry upon creating an image from a
volume right before uploading the volume to glance. This version
however does not aim to do more than add the initial framework and
help with subsequent image downloads. There are certainly more
improvements that can be done over time on top of this.

These image-volumes are host specific, so each backend may end up with
its very own image-volume to do clones from.

The cache is limited in size by number of entries allowed and size in
gb. When creating a new entry if space is needed the last used entries
will be evicted to make room.

In the current implementation the image-volumes will be viewable by a
cloud admin in the volume list, and show up as owned by the Cinder
internal tenant. They can safely be deleted manually by an admin, this
will cause the entry to be removed from the cache. These volumes will
use quota for the internal tenant.

Cache actions will post notifications to Ceilometer. There are
notifications like ‘image_volume_cache.miss’, ‘image_volume_cache.hit’,
and ‘image_volume_cache.evict’. A change will be required to the
event_definitions.yaml to see them nicely. Until then you only need to
add a new event type 'image_volume_cache.*' and look for the ‘image_id’
and ‘host’ fields.

DocImpact: We probably want some instructions on restrictions of the
cache and how to use it. The three new config options should also be
documented somewhere: ‘image_volume_cache_enabled’,
’image_volume_cache_max_size_gb’, ‘image_volume_cache_max_size_count’

Co-Authored-By: Tomoki Sekiyama <tomoki.sekiyama@hds.com>

Implements: blueprint image-volume-cache
Change-Id: If22bbaff89251e4e82a715170a48b4040f95c09f

(3 comments)

Overall, I'm a positive on this. However, we should probably discuss and dig into how the coupling with openstack-ansible/OSAD's inventory system will be handled.

Also, I believe upgrades are as important, if not more, when making changes, so I've added a note to that effect."}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-08-17 17:10:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(7 comments)

I don't think this has been thoroughly thought out. And unlike Nolan, I'm adamant that we need to know the upgrade story before splitting this out."}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-08-17 17:12:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Further, it should be noted that we do not need separate repositories and core-teams for subject matter experts. The community as a whole has embraced a trust model which works as follows:

Someone is a subsystem core and is expected to only +/-2 changes to their subsystem. They can still (obviously) contribute and review other subsystems, but unless they're a core on that subsystem as well, they're trusted to only +/-1 those reviews.

If we want SME cores, we can follow this."}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-08-18 06:43:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-os-ansible-deployment-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/79/213779/5/check/gate-os-ansible-deployment-specs-docs/9686c7f//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 35s'}, {'account_id': 7219, 'date': '2015-09-14 10:28:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

In principle I agree with the concept of breaking the project up into a number of roles.

From reading the spec and comments it seems that this proposal is looking to separate out the roles in their current form and I think that makes the spec premature. I don't believe there has ever been any real discussion on how the project is structured and if there were to be any changes made I believe it would be simpler to do that while everything is in one repo. If the community is is happy with the current structure that discussion shouldn't slow down the implementation of this spec for long, however if there is a decision to change things I think this spec would hinder that effort.

Personally I am currently of the view that each OpenStack service should be represented by a repo that is a collection of playbooks that are responsible installing and upgrading that service. OpenStack-Ansible should aggregate these playbooks and add an opinionated layer on top of them."}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-09-14 10:41:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Harry I Don't think that this spec is premature at all. If you believe so then it seems to me like I haven't expressed clearly enough in the spec that the proposal is to:

1. Allow new roles be registered in separate repositories.

2. Open the door for proposals for existing roles to, through an independent blueprint/spec process, be split from the current monolithic repository into their own repositories.

Is there a way that I can make this clearer? If so, please comment specifically in some of the proposal content."}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-09-14 10:47:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 7219, 'date': '2015-09-14 10:59:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@Jesse - on patchset 3 you agreed with the comment 'I think the initial move is to take the role "as-is" and migrate it to the defined role repository''}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-09-14 11:52:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Harry Yes, that would be a strategy - but also in PS3 I state that each role's move to an independent repository will need to be handled on a case by case basis through its own blueprint. This very same message has been included in the content of the patch and the message improved to be clearer in subsequent patch sets. This is not the focal point of the proposal though - it's only part of it. This has also been made more clear in the subsequent patch sets."}, {'account_id': 7307, 'date': '2015-09-15 09:36:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7307, 'date': '2015-09-15 09:41:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I agree with git-harry that we need some fundamental discussions around how we structure our roles and offload more tasks to playbooks, but I do not personally believe that needs to block this spec.  Either way, I think this project will benefit if we have a mechanism in place to include 3rd party roles and to move infrastructure roles (rabbitmq/galera/memcache) to external repos.  I really hope we can organise a discussion where we draft how we wish to structure roles but I'd like to see this spec move forward in the mean time."}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2015-09-22 02:56:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-22 02:56:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Verified

commit_message:
Add unit tests for signature_utils class

This patch adds unit tests for the signature_utils class,
which adds image signing functionality to Glance.

Depends-On: I0b0592a3526a4e4f5b39ae6ce8b4dedd0ccc31d9

commit_message:
live-migration: Logs exception if operation failed

Live-migration can fail silently, without proper logging, making it
hard to determine the cause of the failure.

Closes-Bug: #1489874

Change-Id: Ib70dafd6fe2658ae9a1a43d177f4ed2c99a10c04

commit_message:
Use admin context in octavia driver, improve logs

When polling for the status of a load balancer in octavia, the context created
by the plugin was being used.  Since the polling takes place in a thread, that
context can have some unexpected behavior.  It is better to create an admin
context in the thread because it definitely exists in that thread.

Also improve debug logging in the octavia driver and the successful and failed
completion helper methods in the mixins.

Change-Id: I6f64c95d89876c9d1d19076a4fe7e3006a0df5e0
Closes-Bug: #1497823

[{'created': '2015-06-15 21:04:18.000000000', 'message': 'Relax newly imposed sql driver restriction for domain config

The first implementation of the domain config API introduced a
new restrction in terms of which identity drivers could be SQL
backed (to avoid potential multi-process race conditions). This
restriction specified that only the default domain could be SQL
backed.

This patch resolves these issues and hence enusres the restrictions
in terms of SQL identity drivers are the same as the original config
file based domain condif approach (i.e. only one driver can be SQL
backend, but it can be any for any given domain).

THIS PATCH IS STILL WORK IN PROGRESS

Fixes bug 1450344

commit_message:
Relax newly imposed sql driver restriction for domain config

The first implementation of the domain config API introduced a
new restriction in terms of which identity drivers could be SQL
backend (to avoid potential multi-process race conditions). This
restriction specified that only the default domain could be SQL
backend.

This patch resolves these issues and hence ensures the restrictions
in terms of SQL identity drivers are the same as the original config
file based approach (i.e. only one driver can be SQL backend, but
it can be for any given domain).

Although this patch changes the V8 driver interface, this is for
the domain_config backend which is still marked as experimental.

Closes-Bug: #1450344
Change-Id: Id1b4415cb5f263dc7afd9e25bd0da2b667f1c90a

Clean up CIMC driver docs and comments

Based on comments on the original commit, this patch fixes a few minor
issues that were picked up.

Change-Id: If71680ac37558caa76cd0e0dae610967485e8a48

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-01 12:27:05.000000000', 'message': "Add Cisco IMC PXE Driver

Current drivers only allow for control of UCS servers via either IPMI or
UCSM, the Cisco UCS C-Series operating in standalone mode can also be
controlled via CIMC using its http/s XML API. This provides finer
control over the server than IPMI can, and doesn't require the extra
infrastructure that UCSM needs.

Change-Id: Ibd39040e3d7e82a87960d33150750433beb2453b
Implements: blueprints cisco-imc-pxe-driver

Implements: blueprint cisco-imc-pxe-driver
"}]
commit_message:
Add Cisco IMC PXE Driver

Current drivers only allow for control of UCS servers via either IPMI or
UCSM, the Cisco UCS C-Series operating in standalone mode can also be
controlled via CIMC using its http/s XML API. This provides finer
control over the server than IPMI can, and doesn't require the extra
infrastructure that UCSM needs.

Change-Id: Ibd39040e3d7e82a87960d33150750433beb2453b
Implements: blueprint cisco-imc-pxe-driver

[{'created': '2015-08-19 07:37:41.000000000', 'message': 'Hyper-V: Implements detach_interface method

Neutron events have been added to nova. If the event
"network-vif-unplugged" is received, the nova compute manager
will proceed to call the compute driver's detach_interface method.
The mentioned method is not implemented in the HyperVDriver,
causing errors.

On Windows Hyper-V / Server 2012 R2 (kernel version 6.4), vNICs
can be attached / detached while the VM are running, if the VM
is generation 2.

Adds detach_interface method implementation.

Closes-Bug: #1486410

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Implements attach_interface and detach_interface method

Neutron events have been added to nova. If the event
"network-vif-unplugged" is received, the nova compute manager
will proceed to call the compute driver's detach_interface method.
The mentioned method is not implemented in the HyperVDriver,
causing errors.

On Windows Hyper-V / Server Threshold (kernel version 10.0), vNICs
can be attached / detached while the VM are running, if the VM
is generation 2.

Adds attach_interface and detach_interface method implementations.

Co-Authored-By: Adelina Tuvenie <atuvenie@cloudbasesolutions.com>

Closes-Bug: #1486410

commit_message:
Remove "shelved_image_id" key from instance system metadata

In the unit test case "test_unshelve_instance_schedule_and_rebuild_volume_backed
", set the "shelved_image_id" to the instance system metadata,
it tests the instance boot from image, not boot from volume.
So it needs to remove "shelved_image_id" from the  metadata,
and remove "image_api.get" mock method.

Change-Id: Ie501acaaa1c961a4b6f1f4ea9726a5b11b0de709
Closes-Bug: #1485429
Signed-off-by: Xiaowei Qian <qianxw.fnst@cn.fujitsu.com>

[{'created': '2015-09-21 14:14:43.000000000', 'message': "Fix reconnecting to libvirt

The libvirt inspector may can't inspect data from libvirt on some occasions after
libvirtd is restarted, though we have reconnecting logic. When this occurs, it will
raise libvirt.VIR_ERR_INTERNAL_ERROR instead of libvirt.VIR_ERR_SYSTEM_ERROR in
reconnecting logic. This results compute agent no longer reconnects to libvirt, and
fails to inspect data any more. This patch is just updated to deal with INTERNAL_ERROR.

Change-Id: Ifbd754cb050ec7e364d17fea3b32191da1e22ef5
Closes-bug: #1498013
"}]
commit_message:
Fix reconnecting to libvirt

The libvirt inspector may can't inspect data from libvirt on some occasions after
libvirtd is restarted, though we have reconnecting logic. When this occurs, it will
raise libvirt.VIR_ERR_INTERNAL_ERROR instead of libvirt.VIR_ERR_SYSTEM_ERROR in
reconnecting logic. This results compute agent no longer reconnects to libvirt, and
fails to inspect data any more. This patch is just updated to deal with INTERNAL_ERROR.

Change-Id: Ifbd754cb050ec7e364d17fea3b32191da1e22ef5
Closes-bug: #1498013

commit_message:
Removing "skip" decorators for some OpenStack actions tests

Bug #1422725 has been fixed and now there is no need to skip
test_heat_actions and test_neutron_actions tests. This patch
removes "skip" decorators for these tests.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-21 18:45:21.000000000', 'message': "Change recon_lock_path to /var/lock

The Swift configuration item [filter:recon]/recon_lock_path is set to
'/var/lock/swift' by openstack-ansible in the appropriate configuration
files. The playbooks also create the directory if it does not exist. If
the host is rebooted the directory '/var/lock/swift' is missing and must
be recreated.

/var/lock (/run/lock) is a tmpfs and so the directory /var/lock/swift
will not persist between reboots.

Swift attempts to create a directory in the directory specified by
recon_lock_path however it does not recursively create any missing
parent directories.

This commit changes the value of [filter:recon]/recon_lock_path to that
set by Swift, '/var/lock'. This allows it to create the directory
'/var/lock/swift-recon-object-cron'. The creation of '/var/lock/swift'
is also removed from the playbooks.

Conflicts:
  playbooks/roles/os_swift/tasks/swift_pre_install.yml
  playbooks/roles/os_swift/templates/account-server.conf.j2
  playbooks/roles/os_swift/templates/container-server.conf.j2
  playbooks/roles/os_swift/templates/object-server.conf.j2

Change-Id: I714367b02c7cf961e9e0bdee4e41f9e4e105b088
Closes-bug: #1496117
(cherry picked from commit 176107aa3026ce03a09bd9a62e7a100e58d2cccc)
"}]
commit_message:
Change recon_lock_path to /var/lock

The Swift configuration item [filter:recon]/recon_lock_path is set to
'/var/lock/swift' by openstack-ansible in the appropriate configuration
files. The playbooks also create the directory if it does not exist. If
the host is rebooted the directory '/var/lock/swift' is missing and must
be recreated.

/var/lock (/run/lock) is a tmpfs and so the directory /var/lock/swift
will not persist between reboots.

Swift attempts to create a directory in the directory specified by
recon_lock_path however it does not recursively create any missing
parent directories.

This commit changes the value of [filter:recon]/recon_lock_path to that
set by Swift, '/var/lock'. This allows it to create the directory
'/var/lock/swift-recon-object-cron'. The creation of '/var/lock/swift'
is also removed from the playbooks.

Conflicts:
  playbooks/roles/os_swift/tasks/swift_pre_install.yml
  playbooks/roles/os_swift/templates/account-server.conf.j2
  playbooks/roles/os_swift/templates/container-server.conf.j2
  playbooks/roles/os_swift/templates/object-server.conf.j2

Change-Id: I714367b02c7cf961e9e0bdee4e41f9e4e105b088
Closes-bug: #1496117
(cherry picked from commit 176107aa3026ce03a09bd9a62e7a100e58d2cccc)

(15 comments)'}, {'account_id': 11303, 'date': '2015-06-08 11:14:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@Joe Gordon:

There are currently multiple wiki pages one has to read to understand 
the process in nova [1][2][3][4]. The process I mean is tightly bound
to the issue tracker (right now "Launchpad") and specifically gaining 
and maintaining an overview of the bugs. I think of it as bookkeeping.
The link you provided contains a mix of 

* description of the bookkeeping of the issue tracker
* requirements of the infrastructure to link issue tracker and code

The first item is indeed a subset of the topics in this review and I
think it shouldn't be covered in the infrastructure docs. I tend to 
believe that every project should adapt a process of "bookkeeping" 
which fits best to their needs. This adaption could lead to changes
in the process of each project. These differences would then be 
difficult to break down on a "general OpenStack bug handling process" 
wiki pages. That's why I think that a nova specific "bookkeeping 
process" in the developer reference makes sense.

To be clear, the second part of your link, which I titled as 
"requirements of the infrastructure to link issue tracker and code"
should stay in the infra project and at best incorporates the 
information of [5], IMO.

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Bugs
[2] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/BugTriage
[3] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Nova/BugTriage
[4] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Bug_Tags
[5] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages'}, {'account_id': 11303, 'date': '2015-06-08 11:15:41.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-08 12:14:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified-1

commit_message:
devref: Add bug handling description to developer reference

The bug handling in nova is described over a few wiki pages. It also
missed some information a new developer would need to understand the
process. An adoption and review of the process with the core reviewers
and the bug-supervisors is hard to do.

This patch set adds a page to the developer reference and should be
the "single source of truth" one needs to read to be able to
participate in the bug handling process of nova.

Partially Implements: blueprint devref-refresh-liberty

Change-Id: I4c306e4201fecc17aee2714e3075b5d1d291a322
Depends-On: Ia699fd1965b475f2633ecfc555bc766eb5aa3404

(8 comments)

Couple of comments inlined.  And my biggest question is: do we need this 'force' flag to set to-be-migrated volume to 'maintanance' status to avoid interruption?  Or another way to ask is: is there any backend that is able to safely/correctly stop a in-progress migration when user issues new operations like 'attach'/'detach'?  I doubt none of existing backend can do that.  So instead of allowing such proven-to-be-failure operation, shouldn't we make it default to set volume to 'maintanace'?"}, {'account_id': 2861, 'date': '2015-07-23 16:23:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 47:

Zhiteng, your concern is exactly what I proposed for this blueprint at first. However, there is another voice from the community that the following case should be considered. The owner A creates the volume vol1 and the cinder migrate command is only accessible to the admin. The admin issues the migration command to this volume vol1. If the volume status is changed to 'maintenance', then the volume service is unavailable to the owner A any longer, which will brings the owner A much confusions. After a discussion during one IRC meeting about one month ago, we decide to go with this approach, which is to add a --force flag to decide if the volume service should be available, if an admin issues the migration command to the volume created by owner A.

If the admin use --force, this will put the volume in 'maintenance', meaning the volume service is out. No other actions is able to do.
If no --force is used, then it is POSSIBLE that other actions, attach/detach, may interrupt the the migration."}, {'account_id': 2861, 'date': '2015-07-23 16:45:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 47:

(1 comment)

My spec was being revised for many time, the final one has the way of the implementations: https://review.openstack.org/186327.

The IRC meeting we discussed this concern is over here: http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/cinder/2015/cinder.2015-06-03-16.00.log.html#16:11:51.
I think you can search the '16:11:51' as the key word to locate the point."}, {'account_id': 2861, 'date': '2015-07-23 17:23:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 47:

(7 comments)'}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2015-07-23 17:25:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 47:

Despite what was decided in the spec, I still find this confusing. A migration occurs whether or not you provide the --force flag, but --force actually means do a migration that is not interruptible.

I prefer the idea of an admin putting the volume into a locked state and then starting a migration instead of having the migration do that. It's less confusing and there may be more uses for the maintenance status in the future. At a minimum change the name of the force flag to --interruptible or something."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-27 21:40:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 50: Verified-1

@Alex, thank you for reviewing the code. So far it is ok for the admin to set the volume status into maintenance to put the volume in a locked state as you mentioned, because I put maintenance into the valid volume state list. You can check it from the patch.

Then I think I can add more comments to better explain the force and the relation between force and interruption. I am also responsible for improving the documents later when the patch lands in our code. Are you ok with it? Simply rename this flag force? I tested 3 cases with this patch:

1. Migrate volume without --lock-volume flag and without any other actions.  
Result: Volume migration was successful.

2. Migrate volume with --lock-volume set to True and attempt to extend volume.  
Result: Volume migration was successful.  Extend volume failed as expected.

The initial migration_status is None, meaning no migration has been
done. Migration_status 'error' means the previous migration fails.
Migration_status 'success' means the previous migration succeeds.

The volume status should be set to 'migrating' during migration and
goes back to its original status after migration.

Change-Id: Ia86421f2d6fce61dcfeb073f8e7b9c9dde517373

"}, {'created': '2015-07-10 04:34:42.000000000', 'message': "Volume status management during migration

The initial migration_status is None, meaning no migration has been
done. Migration_status 'error' means the previous migration failed.
Migration_status 'success' means the previous migration succeeded.

If the --force flag is used, the volume status should be set to
'maintenance' during migration and goes back to its original status
after migration. Otherwise, if the --force flag is not used or set
to True, the volume status will remain the same as its original
status.

All the actions, including attach, detach, etc, are not allowed
when the volume is in 'maintenance' mode. If it is not in maintenance
mode, the migration can be terminated if other requests
are issued, e.g. attach.

DocImpact
APIImpact The --force flag has been added into the API, telling the
volume to change the status to 'maintenance' or not.

Change-Id: Ia86421f2d6fce61dcfeb073f8e7b9c9dde517373
Partially-implements-blueprint: migration-improvement

"}, {'created': '2015-08-14 09:25:27.000000000', 'message': "WIP: Volume status management during migration

The initial migration_status is None, meaning no migration has been
done. Migration_status 'error' means the previous migration failed.
Migration_status 'success' means the previous migration succeeded.

If the key 'lock_volume' is set to True from the request, the volume
status should be set to 'maintenance' during migration and goes
back to its original status after migration. Otherwise, if the
key 'lock_volume' is set to False, the volume status will remain the
same as its original status.

From the REST's perspectives, all the create, update and delete
actions are not allowed if the volume is in 'maintenance', because
it means the volume out of service. If it is not in maintenance
mode, the migration can be interrupted if other requests are
issued, e.g. attach. For the termination of migration, another
patch will target to resolve it.

DocImpact
APIImpact The key 'lock_volume' has been added into the API,
telling the volume to change the status to 'maintenance' or not.

"}, {'created': '2015-08-26 07:55:02.000000000', 'message': "Volume status management during migration

This patch proposes an new implementation for the status and
the migration_status for volumes.

* The initial migration_status is None, meaning no migration has been
done; Migration_status 'error' means the previous migration failed.
Migration_status 'success' means the previous migration succeeded.

* If the key 'lock_volume' is set to True from the request, the volume
status should be set to 'maintenance' during migration and goes
back to its original status after migration. Otherwise, if the
key 'lock_volume' is set to False, the volume status will remain the
same as its original status. The default value for lock_volume is
False and it applies to the available volume.

* From the REST's perspectives, all the create, update and delete
actions are not allowed if the volume is in 'maintenance', because
it means the volume is out of service. If it is not in maintenance
mode, the migration can be interrupted if other requests are
issued, e.g. attach. For the termination of migration, another
patch will target to resolve it.

DocImpact
APIImpact The key 'lock_volume' has been added into the API,
telling the volume to change the status to 'maintenance' or not.
The migration_status has been added into results returned
from volume list command, if the request is from an admin.

Change-Id: Ia86421f2d6fce61dcfeb073f8e7b9c9dde517373
Partial-implements: blueprint migration-improvement

commit_message:
Volume status management during migration

This patch proposes a new implementation for the status and
the migration_status for volumes.

* The initial migration_status is None, meaning no migration has been
done; Migration_status 'error' means the previous migration failed.
Migration_status 'success' means the previous migration succeeded.

* If the key 'lock_volume' is set to True from the request, the volume
status should be set to 'maintenance' during migration and goes
back to its original status after migration. Otherwise, if the
key 'lock_volume' is set to False, the volume status will remain the
same as its original status. The default value for lock_volume is
False and it applies to the available volume.

* From the REST's perspectives, all the create, update and delete
actions are not allowed if the volume is in 'maintenance', because
it means the volume is out of service. If it is not in maintenance
mode, the migration can be interrupted if other requests are
issued, e.g. attach. For the termination of migration, another
patch will target to resolve it.

DocImpact
APIImpact The key 'lock_volume' has been added into the API,
telling the volume to change the status to 'maintenance' or not.
The migration_status has been added into results returned
from volume list command, if the request is from an admin.

Change-Id: Ia86421f2d6fce61dcfeb073f8e7b9c9dde517373
Partial-implements: blueprint migration-improvement

commit_message:
Auto assign nic for servers context

Servers context now uses nova scenarios's _boot_servers. Enable
auto_assign_nic in servers context could avoid "Multiple possible
networks found" error from Nova.

Change-Id: I15a4f1595344331971078cb1e4f17162e764ac8e
Closes-Bug: #1477583

commit_message:
Fix gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-src-python-barbicanclient gate

Gate continues to fail due to the following error:
[ERROR] /opt/stack/new/devstack/inc/python:178 The following
LIBS_FROM_GIT were not installed correct: python-barbicanclient

This patch changes the pre-test hook to install the
python-barbican client from git before the tests are run.

Change-Id: I1ef957a8a85e0762cc90b3aab7299ed9bec86e23

commit_message:
Fix adding tap failure if bridge mapping is not provided

When bridge mapping option is not provided, tap interface cannot be
added properly. The root cause is that linux bridge agent is expecting
bridge mapping option is provided if physical network is presented.

However it is not always the case as Kilo was working fine
without existing bridge mapping

Change-Id: Ie43905887a9bc60858e3edae7fc339a7e0485716
Closes-bug: #1495161

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-21 23:27:12.000000000', 'message': "Make nodepool dsvm experimental

This job is not very reliable yet, so should not be voting.

It also takes significantly longer than other nodepool tests and
is not needed for most nodepool changes.  It is good to be able to
validate nodepool's behavior against a running OpenStack cloud, but
nodepool itself does not change the behavior of the cloud like
the OpenStack components in devstack.  Nor does it rely heavily on
OpenStack features -- instead, it uses a very simple set of API calls
that are well-mocked in nodepool.

Add it to the experimental pipeline so it is easily available to test
changes that alter our use of the OpenStack API.

Change-Id: Id92cb0b3adcfc8fa4db969b5a53bdf8fac49ab7f

commit_message:
Make nodepool dsvm non-voting

This job can fail due to external factors, so make it non-voting.

Change-Id: Id92cb0b3adcfc8fa4db969b5a53bdf8fac49ab7f

Why do this at all? Why not refactor in Liberty if we're going to have to do it anyways. Here's how I look at it. Lets say no one does the refactor work in liberty. I now have something that I merged that's temporary that may introduce bugs and this feature may have bugs later after the major refactor. I'd rather us just spend the energy stabilizing on the main goal and use the sqlalchemy utils code that has been working for us in volumes. Usually I'm fine with this approach, but an iterative approach here doesn't make sense, and ultimately could leave pagination in snapshots inconsistent with volumes."}, {'account_id': 9535, 'date': '2015-07-01 15:24:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Mike, from the client's point of view this pagination is consistent with volume pagination, as it provides the same snapshots_links, rel and href key entries in response.

The only thing that is different is the way returned next url is formed, and that should not matter to receiving end. You want the next page, you follow provided link.

While I see your point, I'm sure you see as well that if nobody refactors this and then adds pagination, as you say, we will keep missing pagination from snapshots. And it is kind of hard to understand not having such a basic feature.

In regards of bugs that this feature may introduce, I have created tempest tests that I believe are good enough to confirm that the feature is quite solid.

By the way, if you construct this kind of url (using offset instead of marker) manually for volumes you will be able to paginate them as well."}, {'account_id': 10327, 'date': '2015-07-02 07:19:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

And if you are doing all that it doesn't make any sense not to refactor it to use _view_builder...  Which brings me back to my comments on the commit message, that is not what this patch does.

[{'created': '2015-06-24 13:09:23.000000000', 'message': "Add pagination to snapshots

Currently snapshot list does not provide pagination like volume does.

This patch adds simple pagination feature using existing API parameters.
Which means it doesn't allow marker optional argument.

It uses already existing limit and offset parameters to generate the
next link and it is returned in the same way as volume does: {
'snapshots': [...], 'snapshots_links': [{'rel': 'next', 'href':
'http...'}]}

Since pagination's slicing is done at API level instead of at DB level,
same as it was done before this patch when using limit and reaching
osapi_max_limit, this is as efficient as it could be, but that will be
left for another patch.

Snapshots need refactoring to use _view_builder like the rest of the
resources do, but again, that should be for another patch.

DocImpact
APIImpact
Change-Id: I21edac6d29abf7fc2f446111a7d6888db9ab6eba

commit_message:
Add pagination to snapshots

Currently snapshot list does not provide pagination like volume does.

This patch adds pagination for snapshots in the same way that volume
does, using marker, limit, sort_keys and sort_dirs.

DocImpact
APIImpact: Use marker, limit, sort_keys and sort_dirs
Implements: snapshots-and-bakcup-support-pagination-query
Implements: blueprint extend-limit-implementations
Change-Id: I21edac6d29abf7fc2f446111a7d6888db9ab6eba

commit_message:
resource failure causes nested stacks to be rolled back

an update_cancel RPC call for a nested stacks whenever an update
operation was cancelled in the parent stack.Unfortunately this always
triggers a rollback.
In this change, resource failure with nested stacks will cancel any
in-progress update but not roll back by default (roll back only when
rollblack cancel exception raised).
The Operator can retry in this way without waiting for timeout
or overall roll back occurred.

Change-Id: I94d75a21367f39c17a9b40b5d23405a28873cd1a
Closes-Bug: #1475057
(cherry picked from commit b76f6ec0e97a9c3aaf5b5140e7a449c9636b8f95)

[{'created': '2015-09-21 01:35:04.000000000', 'message': 'Cancel nested stack updates when appropriate

If a stack update is cancelled while the update of a nested stack is being
processed, the nested stack update is no longer stopped since the
implementation changed in Kilo to use the RPC API to control nested stacks.

To alleviate this, use the RPC API to cancel the (nested) stack update when
the resource update is cancelled. This results in a rollback of the nested
stack, so if a subsequent attempt to roll back the ensted stack by doing a
stack update fails due to the rollback already being in progress, just
ignore the error and wait for the existing operation to complete.

Closes-Bug: #1446252

'}]
commit_message:
Cancel nested stack updates when appropriate

If a stack update is cancelled while the update of a nested stack is being
processed, the nested stack update is no longer stopped since the
implementation changed in Kilo to use the RPC API to control nested stacks.

To alleviate this, use the RPC API to cancel the (nested) stack update when
the resource update is cancelled. This results in a rollback of the nested
stack, so if a subsequent attempt to roll back the ensted stack by doing a
stack update fails due to the rollback already being in progress, just
ignore the error and wait for the existing operation to complete.

Conflicts:
	heat/engine/resources/stack_resource.py

Change-Id: I3eacf216194517c995732a3f4de876551b70fe91
Closes-Bug: #1446252
(cherry picked from commit ad4c00e672fdd2c1c8461d7e4813dff4b093ae0f)

commit_message:
test_l2_ovs_agent: _bind_port fixes

- Don't use an uuid as an ofport number
- Don't call _bind_devices repeatedly for same ports
- Simplifications

Closes-Bug: #1475498
Change-Id: Ib008ed87162f0fbb0818ddd56cc70aa4b03ffa8d

commit_message:
claims: move a debug msg to a warn on missing migration

We want to log a warning when there is a missing migration record when
creating a migration_context record, because it's most likely caused by
either a misconfiguration or a bug. We made it a debug message in the
original patch as the rules for translated strings were unclear at the
time, but now we can do it - so let's do it!

Change-Id: I440e357f8eeacae2972c74aa7be15d689fb9ac64

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Fixes serial port issue on Windows Threshold

On Windows Threshold, a new WMI class was introduced, targeting
VM serial ports.

For this reason, attempting to retrieve serial port connections
fails on Windows Threshold.

This patch fixes the issue by adding an extra check and using the
right WMI class in order to retrieve VM serial ports.

Change-Id: Ibaf6ac2e77b6324538c6f3dbaacab2a5f065b4ce
Closes-Bug: #1466056
(cherry picked from commit b645a752707dffbfce97a39c456509439614f3b6)

commit_message:
Prepare tempest job for ironic-lib

ironic-lib will soon become a dependency of ironic. To avoid future
breakages we decided to act in advance, and prepare a dsvm job for it.

Non-voting for now, will make voting as soon as it proves working.

Depends-On: I6e66ae770cf5065980848e7e987bfd75765a5ac6
Change-Id: Icb7a02b3dd76a1e1663b73855f39895cb2ee5db6

commit_message:
Add a non-voting gate-barbican-python34 check job

Barbican has a py34 test environment in tox.ini, but no check job
associated job. Because of that, a Python 3 regression was
reintroduced and nobody noticed. Having a check job would help to
detect earlier such error.

The next step will be to make the gate voting to ensure that Python 3
regressions cannot be reintroduced anymore.

Note: The change I41764d39a1dab95df47485efa3a9ea0868d93036 should fix
"tox -e py34" in Barbican.

Partially-Implements: blueprint barbican-py3
Change-Id: I8ce646aaca97b04741649f863a744fbd389198a6

commit_message:
Add docs and PyPI publishing for networking-bgpvpn

This change adds standard docs and PyPI publishing as per sub-project
guidelines. It also corrects a gramatical nit in the project
description. The PyPI project has been created with the matching name
networking-bgpvpn.

Change-Id: I278536775461985b52d8186717efeb8c520f15d3

[{'created': '2015-09-19 17:04:07.000000000', 'message': 'Better message about updates available

Message used can easily scare off: if Fuel installs without
errors, there are should not be any warnings. We had warning
even if both installation is successful and Internet is
available for updates. I propose to change it to notice
(same type of message which is used for "Master node installation has
been completed successfully").

Related-Bug: #1495658
'}]
commit_message:
Better message about updates available

Message used can easily scare off: if Fuel installs without
errors, there are should not be any warnings. We had warning
even if both installation is successful and Internet is
available for updates. I propose to change it to notice
(same type of message which is used for "Master node installation has
been completed successfully").

Change-Id: If7911f9a28d7d1d5977819a01612b051cd4e0e72
Related-Bug: #1495658

commit_message:
adds the config_template to galera_client

The change modifies the galera_client template tasks such that it's now
using the config_template action plugin. This change will make so that
config files can be dynamically updated, by a deployer, at run time,
without requiring the need to modify the in tree templates or defaults.

Partially implements: blueprint tunable-openstack-configuration

Change-Id: Ia798607268d874a50e3c2f2cddbb9512d74df3ca

commit_message:
Adds more unit_tests, bug fixes for API

This change adds additional unit tests for the REST API methods
get_test_runs, get_runs_from_build_name, get_tests_from_run,
get_run_test_runs. Also fixes a typo and adds dict conversion in the
API method get_run_test_runs.

Co-Authored-By: Matthew Treinish <mtreinish@kortar.org>
Change-Id: I20cee83f48da2b4f6ab6f4167fd35cc8fe8cfe8d

Andrey, it is fairly simple. The initial code that introduced this regression was trying to fix the issue with the same test where nodes were lacking memory. It was 90% rewritten. The test is really easy to create - just kill rabbitmq daemon and beam virtual machine. It will return ERR_GENERIC on next monitor. After that do it on each node - you will get into the situation when pacemaker will not try to start anything until you clean it up.'}, {'account_id': 6926, 'date': '2015-09-15 18:03:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Vladimir, "kill rabbitmq daemon and beam virtual machine. It will return ERR_GENERIC on next monitor. After that do it on each node - you will get into the situation when pacemaker will not try to start anything until you clean it up"

I did that many times, and every time resource was recovered by pacemaker. So I agree there is must be test reproducing the related bug 100%.'}, {'account_id': 8786, 'date': '2015-09-16 12:02:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Bogdan, yes, you will get ERR_GENERIC, after which it will try to stop it and start it. But! . But it will eventually get into state when it is getting more and more false-negative ERR_GENERIC statuses raising failcount, thus blocking ability to start the resource until you clean the things up.'}, {'account_id': 8786, 'date': '2015-09-16 12:05:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Return NOT_RUNNING when beam is not RUNNING

Change get_status to return NOT_RUNNING when
beam is not_running. Otherwise, pacemaker
will get stuck during rabbitmq failover and
will not attempt to restart the failed resource

Change-Id: I926a3eafa9968abdf07baa5f2d5c22480300fb30
Closes-bug: #1484280

Just do the error logging in the base exception

We want to make an error log every time we throw an exception that
is wrapping another exception. So, just do it in the constructor.

Change-Id: Id8f1ab97d1c58787ff101ea2410fcf7c789041ed

commit_message:
Adding Functional Tests and Supporting Fixes for Global Preferred CAs

This commit containers the following changes to fix the global
preferred certificate authority operations.

- Add functional tests for global preferred CA operations
- Change cas/CA_ID/unset-global-preferred to cas/unset-global-preferred
- Allow all content types for set-global-preferred and unset-global-preferred
- Add create_or_update_from_project_id() for PreferredCertificateAuthority
  table and refactor
- Make reserved global project id an external project id
- Use hard delete for PreferredCertificateAuthority entities

Change-Id: I56fbdb0246f3159444778cd37d0080f771eb00f6
Partially-implements: blueprint add-cas
APIImpact:

commit_message:
Add auth version for legacy OpenStack clients

Adding this environment variable expands Identity v3 coverage for legacy
OpenStack CLI clients. This corrects the authentication URLs used even
if v2 is still being used.

Change-Id: I68197ffd12d71a437c482f13520b83cb08d4c9de
Closes-Bug: #1495685
(cherry-picked from commit f9ea209e12)

commit_message:
Prepare Schema Model API for the new architecture

Schema Model API used DataSourceManager class to return a schema
of datasource or its table. DatasourceManager will be removed in
the new architecture since each datasource works in each process.

This patch changes Schema Model API not to use DataSourceManager's
method.

Change-Id: I3d8e0306422ad77a58734c65dd8494f110024ff6
Partially-Implements: blueprint dist-api-rpcify-schema

[{'created': '2014-11-26 23:31:25.000000000', 'message': 'Support os-endpoint-type

Ceilometerclient will always get publicURL even though we specify
endpoint type via arguments, it is because we call kesytone session
with wrong keyword argument, which should be interface rather than
endpoint_type.

see: https://github.com/openstack/python-keystoneclient/blob/master/keystoneclient/auth/identity/base.py

Change-Id: Ic2b03bd900d913c7efd22c9b91dfaa79e0cdd4bc
Closes-Bug: #1396493
'}]
commit_message:
Support os-endpoint-type

Ceilometerclient will always get publicURL even though we specify
endpoint type via arguments, it is because we call kesytone session
with wrong keyword argument, which should be interface rather than
endpoint_type.

see: https://github.com/openstack/python-keystoneclient/blob/master/keystoneclient/auth/identity/base.py

Change-Id: Ic2b03bd900d913c7efd22c9b91dfaa79e0cdd4bc
Closes-Bug: #1396493

commit_message:
Support base64 padding in federated tokens

Fernet tokens can have base64 padding, which gets urlencoded as one
or more "%3D" strings at the end of the token. This change expands the
parsing of tokens to support the % character.

Change-Id: I62ff7bd94b475cddbc3cfcc7782ce4ef3b65b268

commit_message:
Use format_list instead of format_dict when listing images

This currently breaks listing images with --long. Tags are an
array and shouldn't be formatted as a dictionary.

Change-Id: I6d1d85351b58ae4824498774673ebdc8eaa7e420
Closes-Bug: #1498150

commit_message:
Format an images properties and tags

Currently, these properties are each top level keys, they should
all be under a single 'properties' field. Secondly, the tags are
kept as an array, but can be shown as a comma separated string.

Change-Id: Ic769c657a86e768fee38acc40434c377de70a7bc

Hi Romil, 

  I wanted to add some references to this usage of the host= parameter.

https://github.com/openstack-packages/neutron/blob/rpm-master/NeutronScale.ocf_ra

and

https://github.com/redhat-openstack/astapor/blob/master/puppet/modules/quickstack/manifests/pacemaker/neutron.pp#L241


For HA there are several methods:

1) Manualy re-scheduling resources via scripts from one agent to the new spawned ones
2) Use neutron scheduler to reschedule agents when one host goes down.
3) Using a virtual "hostname" you can roam
4) use HA-routers (only routing)
5) use DVR (only routing)
6) use multiple dhcp agents.

still for 4 and 6 you can benefit from doing roaming hostnames. And for other agents not supporting automatic rescheduling or internal HA, you only can do 2 or 3.

I'm sorry to insist so much, but we're breaking deployments as they upgrade to Kilo because a protection that is only set to protect the administrator from shooting himself on the foot, while admin can do this in many different ways.

If we want to protect from erroneous local_ip settings on agents, I find more reasonable to add a check to the agent to make sure at least one system interface has such IP address before sending it to neutron-server.

Kindly, 
Miguel Ángel Ajo.

BTW: Don't get me wrong, your initial patch is very valuable because otherwise as hosts moved or went in/out the tunnel list got cluttered by unused tunnel endpoints, and so the nodes did.., but the extra constraint is not mandatory IMHO.'}, {'account_id': 10370, 'date': '2015-06-12 08:41:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

Hi Ajo,

Thanks for the detailed justification.
I am fine if we could prevent this at the agent level itself.

Already, there is bug on this, https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1408603.

But, still I would like to know the other reviewer's opinion on this."}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-06-12 09:08:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

@romil, I believe you're missing this:

1) you have hostA: ip1
    you register hostA: ip2

if you delete by ip "ip2", you will have hostA replicated in the DB.
if you delete by "ip1", you could be deleting hostB which took "ip1" in the meanwhile (race condition).

So you need to delete anything containing "hostA" or anything containing "ip2"'}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2015-06-16 13:07:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

a bug where host name changes broke tunneling endpoint updates.
Tunneling endpoint updates changing roaming a hostname from IP

and should happen automatically without the need for API/CLI

delete_endpoint_by_host_or_ip is introduced to allow cleanup of
endpoints that potentially belonged to the newly registered agent,

2) hostA goes offline

4) hostA goes online, with ip2, and registers

commit_message:
Fix hostname roaming for ml2 tunnel endpoints.

Change I75c6581fcc9f47a68bde29cbefcaa1a2a082344e introduced
a bug where host name changes broke tunneling endpoint updates.
Tunneling endpoint updates roaming a hostname from IP to IP
are a common method for active/passive HA with pacemaker and
should happen automatically without the need for API/CLI calls [1].

delete_endpoint_by_host_or_ip is introduced to allow cleanup of
endpoints that potentially belonged to the newly registered agent,
while preventing the race condition found when deleting ip1 & ip2
in the next situation at step 4:

1) we have hostA: ip1
2) hostA goes offline
3) hostB goes online, with ip1, and registers
4) hostA goes online, with ip2, and registers

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/python-neutronclient/+bug/1381664

Change-Id: I04d08d5b82ce9911f3af555b5776fc9823e0e5b6
Closes-Bug: #1464178

commit_message:
Store the inner exception when creating an OSCException

Masking exceptions in Python is an anti-pattern.  Etc.

However, since shade uses a base class of OpenStackCloudException
for all of its exceptions (and, for the worst offenders of
generalized exception masking, simply uses that exception itself),
we can store the original exception for clients to access if needed.

This does allow client exceptions to leak out of shade to its users,
but in a very controlled manner where we can make it clear that
this should not be used for flow control, but for informational
purposes.

Change-Id: I33269743a8f62b863569130aba3cc9b5a8539aa0

[{'created': '2015-09-21 18:04:11.000000000', 'message': "Change recon_lock_path to /var/lock

The Swift configuration item [filter:recon]/recon_lock_path is set to
'/var/lock/swift' by openstack-ansible in the appropriate configuration
files. The playbooks also create the directory if it does not exist. If
the host is rebooted the directory '/var/lock/swift' is missing and must
be recreated.

/var/lock (/run/lock) is a tmpfs and so the directory /var/lock/swift
will not persist between reboots.

Swift attempts to create a directory in the directory specified by
recon_lock_path however it does not recursively create any missing
parent directories.

This commit changes the value of [filter:recon]/recon_lock_path to that
set by Swift, '/var/lock'. This allows it to create the directory
'/var/lock/swift-recon-object-cron'. The creation of '/var/lock/swift'
is also removed from the playbooks.

Change-Id: I714367b02c7cf961e9e0bdee4e41f9e4e105b088
Closes-bug: #1496117
(cherry picked from commit 176107aa3026ce03a09bd9a62e7a100e58d2cccc)
"}]
commit_message:
Change recon_lock_path to /var/lock

The Swift configuration item [filter:recon]/recon_lock_path is set to
'/var/lock/swift' by openstack-ansible in the appropriate configuration
files. The playbooks also create the directory if it does not exist. If
the host is rebooted the directory '/var/lock/swift' is missing and must
be recreated.

/var/lock (/run/lock) is a tmpfs and so the directory /var/lock/swift
will not persist between reboots.

Swift attempts to create a directory in the directory specified by
recon_lock_path however it does not recursively create any missing
parent directories.

This commit changes the value of [filter:recon]/recon_lock_path to that
set by Swift, '/var/lock'. This allows it to create the directory
'/var/lock/swift-recon-object-cron'. The creation of '/var/lock/swift'
is also removed from the playbooks.

Change-Id: I714367b02c7cf961e9e0bdee4e41f9e4e105b088
Closes-bug: #1496117
(cherry picked from commit 176107aa3026ce03a09bd9a62e7a100e58d2cccc)

commit_message:
Adds the config_template to cinder

The change modifies the cinder template tasks such that it's now
using the config_template action plugin. This change will make so that
config files can be dynamically updated, by a deployer, at run time,
without requiring the need to modify the in tree templates or defaults.

Partially implements: blueprint tunable-openstack-configuration

Change-Id: I463bbd3e10895dc2e7788346493f78bc46e5f26e

commit_message:
Adds group support to inventory-manage.py

Added -g for showing groups per instance and -G for showing instances
per group.

Also fixed up some pep8 and pylint issues.

Closes-Bug: 1482141

Change-Id: I698384467268336ecc74f865ee35f3e39cad5186

commit_message:
Change the way of Mistral installation in the mistral-rally gate

Not so long ago Mistral has switched its way of installation
in devstack. Now it installs as devstack plugin.

Change-Id: I5c14425b2abb8f1d61b2cc803badac8810f48dc1

commit_message:
Get runs by date

Extend the runs API with start_date and stop_date parameters to
allow filtering the list of runs by date. The filter is passed
down into the db_api.

Change-Id: I3f48c12f9215bb7c59a0e83b3f90478f0039a158
Depends-on: I9865c4bdc3fee05aa38a87c85528c7a56b71260d

commit_message:
Allow to filter artifacts by range

This code enables filtering properties by range by providing
several parameters, that now considered as concatination,rather
than using only the latest one.

Example: /v3/artifacts/some_type/?property=gt:1&property=lt:10
Returns all the artifacts having the value of "property" greater
than 1 and less than 10.

ApiImpact
FastTrack

Closes-Bug: #1480392

Change-Id: I6fda6b0b6ee6a1da1d0eba8fa9f766e74c4e70d4

subject: Fixed version unequality artifact filtering

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-18 13:31:18.000000000', 'message': 'Fixed version unequality artifact filtering

When filtered by the value of version field artifact list was ignoring
the filtering operators other then equality. I.e. it was possible to
list only artifacts having the version equal to some specific value, but
not the artifacts having the version less then or greater then some
value.

To implement the proper filtering a CompositeProperty comparator was
added which filters the ORM entities in the lexigraphical order of
version fields: first by version prefix, and then - if prefixes are
equal - by version suffix.

Closes-bug: #1480393

commit_message:
Fixed version unequality artifact filtering

When filtered by the value of version field artifact list was ignoring
the filtering operators other then equality. I.e. it was possible to
list only artifacts having the version equal to some specific value, but
not the artifacts having the version less then or greater then some
value.

To implement the proper filtering a CompositeProperty comparator was
added which filters the ORM entities in the lexigraphical order of
version fields: first by version prefix, and then - if prefixes are
equal - by version suffix.

Closes-bug: #1480393
FastTrack

Change-Id: I67ae323e2b74745d794442d71b020becc494646b

property was broken: the code which was intended to do it was trying to

error.

This patch fixes this issue, making sure the filtering on queries like
?property-name=key or ?property-name=key.value is working properly.

commit_message:
Artifacts are now properly filtered by dict props

The ability to filter the artifacts list by the dict-based type-specific
property was broken: the code which was intended to do it was trying to
filter by 'name' property for some reason, thus returning an HTTP 500
error.

This patch fixes this issue, making sure the filtering on queries like
?property-name=key or ?property-name.key=value is working properly.

FastTrack
Closes-bug: #1479700

Change-Id: I22adf9f8a2b69dc15cf1974c00be873b90e5e0d6

Well, new release of pbr.

The runtime API isn't the one in question here - the reason the tests were able to pass is because the buildtime API is also changed when a dep is installed."}]

commit_message:
Pin pbr<1.8 which ignores Sphinx warnerrors

By setting pbr.warnerros = True, Sphinx will fail the build on any
warnings ensuring the documentation is properly maintained.

Due to a bug in pbr 1.8.0, the setting is not recognized when using
Sphinx < 1.3.1 https://bugs.launchpad.net/pbr/+bug/1496882

Since the global-requirements.txt has Sphinx<1.3, it is hit by the bug
and that cause gates to leak Sphinx warnings in repos.

Another way would be to bump Sphinx>=1.3.1 and maybe pbr>=1.8, but that
seems to be a terrible idea.

Restrict pbr to not be above 1.8.
When the bug is fixed, pbr 1.8.0 will need to be blacklisted until
Sphinx is bumped to >=1.3.1.

Change-Id: I3e0a9b625d99d2beb117554948ea738a8fb9047b

commit_message:
Timebox a workaround for v2 image uploads

python-openstackclient has missing support for v2 image uploads, which
means we need to work around it here. v2 image upload support should be
an easy add though, so let's not let it linger.

Change-Id: Iad866f9c8cc122354a1071d139ac0bedc2b1d3ef

Remove the Image API v1 workaround

workaround that uses v1 to upload images.

commit_message:
Do not create config file for ovs2ovs patchcord

Ubuntu with OVS < 2.4 does not support such configs at all.

Change-Id: I9161e282f285dffc018a9d7d3fe91cb3760486ad
Closes-bug: #1495534

commit_message:
Use mistral plugin installation in murano integration gates

After a switch to devstack plugin, gate with murano/mistral/congress
becomes red because of mistral doesn't installed in gate.
This happened after this patch im mistral:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/216729/

This patch adds plugin-style installation in murano/mistral/congress gate

Change-Id: I7cc4ab90a2dce9293fa763b9b07a3ff4039f2d8a

commit_message:
Ensure request variables have corresponding mappings

If a request variable doesn't have the proper direct mapping we
should handle the failure by raising a more detailed exception.
Otherwise when the direct mapping is being processed it will try
to match to a corresponding mappings, resulting in a generic
'IndexError'

Change-Id: I5ffdf55aea050a405cfe298a16e433a987a1c1a1
Co-Authored-By: Christopher J. Schaefer <cjschaef@us.ibm.com>
Closes-Bug: 1474660

commit_message:
Only call isotime on datetime objects

If expires is a str then isinstance six.text_type is false and
the following exception is raised:
AttributeError: 'str' object has no attribute 'strftime'
This change explicitly checks for a datetime object, which is what
timeutils.isotime expects.

Change-Id: Ia31c80b4ae6c2dd7c2e00f69ee5ff1602edbb42d
Closes-Bug: #1490743

On OpenStack deployments with an excess of 1,000 provisioned
VMs, the libvirt plugin may not publish metrics for some or
all of the hosted VMs on each compute node.  This is due to
the default osapi_max_limit of 1000, limiting the number of
results from a Nova API query.

Instead of loading instance data for all Nova VMs, this change
limits the query to just VMs hosted on the local compute node.  It
assumes the hostname in agent.yaml matches the hostname in used by
